1
00:01:08,802 --> 00:01:10,565
He's coming! He's coming!

2
00:01:42,435 --> 00:01:43,959
All right, now.

3
00:01:44,104 --> 00:01:46,937
Let's give a good
Colorado welcome here!

4
00:01:51,811 --> 00:01:54,609
- Hello, sir. You're most welcome.
- Thank you, thank you.

5
00:01:54,781 --> 00:01:56,612
All right, everybody, listen up.

6
00:01:56,783 --> 00:02:00,947
I want to introduce you
to Oscar Wilde.

7
00:02:03,623 --> 00:02:06,649
Welcome to
the Matchless Silver Mine.

8
00:02:06,759 --> 00:02:09,057
Today, we opened up a new seam.

9
00:02:09,195 --> 00:02:11,322
We're gonna name it after you.

10
00:02:11,431 --> 00:02:12,898
How very kind.

11
00:02:13,032 --> 00:02:15,330
I look forward to collecting
the royalties.

12
00:02:18,204 --> 00:02:20,570
Now, why don't you
follow me over here.

13
00:02:20,707 --> 00:02:24,507
Great lecture you gave last night.
We're honored to have you visit us.

14
00:02:26,846 --> 00:02:29,872
If you'd just like to step in here.
There ya go, sir.

15
00:02:50,436 --> 00:02:52,495
I thought I was descending
into hell...

16
00:02:52,605 --> 00:02:56,598
but with these angel faces to greet me,
it must be paradise.

17
00:02:56,709 --> 00:02:59,007
Is this the way to my personal seam?

18
00:02:59,179 --> 00:03:02,171
Of course, I should have preferred
gold-- purple and gold.

19
00:03:02,248 --> 00:03:04,682
But we live in a Silver Age, alas.

20
00:03:06,619 --> 00:03:09,816
So much that is exquisitely beautiful
is wrought from suffering, from pain...

21
00:03:09,923 --> 00:03:14,053
from toil-- broken bones
and blistered skin.

22
00:03:14,194 --> 00:03:16,788
Benevenuto Cellini understood silver.

23
00:03:16,963 --> 00:03:19,591
He took the metal that you mine
so nobly down here...

24
00:03:19,766 --> 00:03:22,894
and transformed it into works of art
for popes and princes.

25
00:03:23,002 --> 00:03:25,300
Cellini-- is he a wop?

26
00:03:25,438 --> 00:03:28,032
The Renaissance man, in every sense.

27
00:03:28,208 --> 00:03:30,938
The greatest silversmith
the world has ever seen...

28
00:03:31,110 --> 00:03:33,704
but a genius in life
as well as art.

29
00:03:33,846 --> 00:03:37,145
He experimented with
every vice known to man.

30
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:39,150
- He committed murder.
- He killed a man?

31
00:03:39,319 --> 00:03:40,718
More than one.

32
00:03:46,459 --> 00:03:49,121
Thank you.

33
00:03:50,463 --> 00:03:53,261
I'd like to meet Cellini.
Why didn't you bring him with you?

34
00:03:53,433 --> 00:03:55,094
I'm afraid he's dead.

35
00:03:55,268 --> 00:03:56,929
Who shot him?

36
00:04:52,592 --> 00:04:55,083
Is Miss Lloyd connected
to Lloyd's Bank?

37
00:04:57,864 --> 00:04:59,195
A pity.

38
00:04:59,332 --> 00:05:01,323
But she's comfortable, Ada.

39
00:05:01,434 --> 00:05:03,026
A thousand a year.

40
00:05:03,202 --> 00:05:05,227
Then I congratulate you, Lady Wilde.

41
00:05:05,338 --> 00:05:08,899
Now that Oscar's been to America
and sown his Wildean oats...

42
00:05:09,042 --> 00:05:10,737
it's time he settled down.

43
00:05:10,910 --> 00:05:12,502
But weren't they very rough?

44
00:05:12,679 --> 00:05:14,943
No, charming.
Well, charming to me.

45
00:05:15,048 --> 00:05:17,175
With each other, it's true
they could be a little brusque.

46
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:20,582
They hanged two men in the theater
one night before I gave a lecture.

47
00:05:20,687 --> 00:05:23,087
I felt like the sorbet
after a side of beef.

48
00:05:26,693 --> 00:05:29,992
I know your friend is famous, Ada--
notorious, at least--

49
00:05:30,096 --> 00:05:32,690
but I don't understand for what.

50
00:05:32,865 --> 00:05:35,766
For being himself,
Lady Mount-Temple.

51
00:05:35,935 --> 00:05:38,199
Don't Americans talk
the most wonderful slang, though?

52
00:05:38,338 --> 00:05:40,533
Well, I did hear one lady say...

53
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:43,131
''After the heel-lick
I shifted my day goods.''

54
00:05:43,276 --> 00:05:45,744
What on earth did she mean?

55
00:05:45,878 --> 00:05:48,142
She meant that she changed
her clothes after a dance.

56
00:05:49,282 --> 00:05:54,310
Connie, my love, Lady Mount-Temple
is so anxious to meet you.

57
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:56,251
I knew your father, Miss Lloyd.

58
00:05:56,422 --> 00:06:00,518
She's delightful, and not stupid.
Really, not stupid at all.

59
00:06:00,626 --> 00:06:03,459
Is that quite a reason to marry her?

60
00:06:03,629 --> 00:06:05,529
Well, I must marry someone.

61
00:06:07,633 --> 00:06:10,295
And my mother has our future
planned out in every detail:

62
00:06:10,470 --> 00:06:13,928
I'm to go into Parliament,
we're to have a nice house...

63
00:06:14,073 --> 00:06:16,507
and live a proper, settled life--
literature, lectures...

64
00:06:16,642 --> 00:06:19,907
the House of Commons, receptions
for the world in general at 5:00.

65
00:06:20,012 --> 00:06:21,240
How dreary.

66
00:06:21,381 --> 00:06:24,009
Your attendance will
not be required at those.

67
00:06:24,183 --> 00:06:27,482
But your sphinxiness will be essential
for our intimate little dinners at 8:00.

68
00:06:27,587 --> 00:06:30,351
It will be a grand life,
a charming life.

69
00:06:31,524 --> 00:06:34,015
I see Constance will be busy
preparing the dinners...

70
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:36,560
but what will she contribute
to the literature and lectures?

71
00:06:36,696 --> 00:06:38,527
She'll correct the proofs
of my articles.

72
00:06:38,698 --> 00:06:40,563
Oh, what a little sunbeam.

73
00:06:48,641 --> 00:06:51,769
I do love her, Ada. She's--

74
00:06:51,878 --> 00:06:54,005
Silent.

75
00:06:54,113 --> 00:06:57,378
- I find her very silent.
- But so sympathetic.

76
00:06:58,518 --> 00:07:00,383
And I do need an audience.

77
00:07:37,924 --> 00:07:41,826
I don't see how you can possibly
take it all in, reading at that speed.

78
00:07:43,229 --> 00:07:44,696
Try me.

79
00:07:44,831 --> 00:07:46,822
I know better.

80
00:07:51,571 --> 00:07:53,232
Where are we dining tonight?

81
00:07:53,406 --> 00:07:54,930
At the Leversons.

82
00:07:55,074 --> 00:07:59,135
Then you must show your true colors
as a propagandist for dress reform.

83
00:07:59,245 --> 00:08:01,770
The cinnamon
cashmere trousers, I think.

84
00:08:01,914 --> 00:08:04,474
And the cape with the ends
that turn up into sleeves.

85
00:08:05,785 --> 00:08:08,811
I don't think I can wear
those trousers anymore.

86
00:08:16,028 --> 00:08:17,859
A new Wilde for the world!

87
00:08:18,030 --> 00:08:19,861
Another genius for Ireland!

88
00:08:23,636 --> 00:08:27,003
We shall have to buy you
a whole new wardrobe.

89
00:08:36,549 --> 00:08:38,710
Ernest proposed to me
under that statue.

90
00:08:38,818 --> 00:08:41,878
Really, the things that go on in front
of works of art are quite appalling.

91
00:08:41,988 --> 00:08:43,751
The police should interfere.

92
00:08:43,923 --> 00:08:48,053
We were made not to marry,
whereas you and Constance are so happy.

93
00:08:48,160 --> 00:08:49,525
Everyone says so.

94
00:08:49,662 --> 00:08:52,722
It's perfectly monstrous how people
say things behind one's back...

95
00:08:52,832 --> 00:08:54,356
that are absolutely true.

96
00:08:55,635 --> 00:08:58,798
So your audience has proved
as responsive as you hoped?

97
00:08:58,905 --> 00:09:01,999
Receptive, yes. Responsive?

98
00:09:02,108 --> 00:09:03,939
I always wonder what she's thinking.

99
00:09:04,110 --> 00:09:07,341
I expect it's about the baby.

100
00:09:07,446 --> 00:09:10,006
Yes. Well, Constance is
such a natural mother.

101
00:09:10,149 --> 00:09:13,949
She's invited Robbie into the nest
while his parents are abroad.

102
00:09:15,288 --> 00:09:18,189
Robbie is Canadian.
You can tell by his youth.

103
00:09:19,358 --> 00:09:22,191
Have you been brought
to England to mature, Mr. Ross?

104
00:09:22,361 --> 00:09:25,819
Well, that was the idea,
but it doesn't seem to be working.

105
00:09:25,965 --> 00:09:29,799
I've lived here since I was three,
and you see the pitiful result.

106
00:09:29,969 --> 00:09:32,563
Robbie comes from a long line
of imperial governors.

107
00:09:32,738 --> 00:09:35,070
His grandfather was
Prime Minister of Upper Canada.

108
00:09:35,207 --> 00:09:36,572
Or was it Lower Canada?

109
00:09:36,709 --> 00:09:39,143
The British will take their class system
with them wherever they go.

110
00:09:39,278 --> 00:09:41,109
They apply it even to continents.

111
00:09:41,280 --> 00:09:43,475
Are you planning
to govern a continent?

112
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:46,916
No. I don't even plan
to govern myself.

113
00:09:54,160 --> 00:09:56,754
Very nicely turned leg.

114
00:09:56,896 --> 00:09:59,194
Hello, sir.

115
00:10:01,233 --> 00:10:04,464
Shall I give you these, my love?
I'll see if I can find a cab.

116
00:10:04,604 --> 00:10:06,936
Coming through there, gents.
Mind your backs.

117
00:10:17,083 --> 00:10:19,608
Can you move
out of the way, please?

118
00:10:29,862 --> 00:10:31,227
Looking for someone?

119
00:10:35,401 --> 00:10:37,392
Cab, cab!

120
00:10:46,445 --> 00:10:47,810
Bedtime.

121
00:10:48,781 --> 00:10:50,373
Just one more cigarette.

122
00:10:56,422 --> 00:10:58,481
No. No, thanks, Robbie.

123
00:11:03,929 --> 00:11:05,988
Don't stay up too late, Robbie.

124
00:11:07,533 --> 00:11:09,831
Good night.

125
00:11:13,439 --> 00:11:15,168
Good night, Oscar.

126
00:11:16,409 --> 00:11:17,774
Good night, Robbie.

127
00:11:33,926 --> 00:11:35,291
He's asleep.

128
00:11:39,899 --> 00:11:41,491
He's so beautiful.

129
00:11:45,171 --> 00:11:47,537
Almost as beautiful
as his mother.

130
00:11:50,042 --> 00:11:54,638
I don't know what I'd do without you,
my constant Constance.

131
00:12:15,034 --> 00:12:16,501
Good night, my dear.

132
00:12:17,937 --> 00:12:19,529
Good night.

133
00:12:40,226 --> 00:12:42,956
A university education
is an admirable thing, of course...

134
00:12:43,129 --> 00:12:46,496
so long as you remember that nothing
worth knowing can ever be taught...

135
00:12:46,632 --> 00:12:48,361
least of all at Cambridge.

136
00:12:48,534 --> 00:12:50,365
But you told me...

137
00:12:50,536 --> 00:12:54,404
in ancient Greece the older men
taught the younger.

138
00:12:54,573 --> 00:12:56,097
They drew them out.

139
00:12:57,409 --> 00:13:00,037
I look forward to being
drawn out immensely.

140
00:13:01,247 --> 00:13:04,148
Yes, well, Greek love--
platonic love--

141
00:13:04,316 --> 00:13:08,412
is the highest form of affection
known to man, of course.

142
00:13:08,521 --> 00:13:10,250
You also told me...

143
00:13:10,422 --> 00:13:13,152
that the Greeks put statues of Apollo
in the bride's chamber...

144
00:13:13,325 --> 00:13:15,793
so she would have beautiful sons.

145
00:13:17,263 --> 00:13:22,064
But I can't help noticing that here
the statue's in your bedroom.

146
00:13:24,236 --> 00:13:25,828
Constance prefers a bath.

147
00:13:43,255 --> 00:13:46,452
She was so beautiful
when I married her, Robbie.

148
00:13:46,559 --> 00:13:49,119
Slim, white as a lily...

149
00:13:49,261 --> 00:13:50,922
such dancing eyes.

150
00:13:51,096 --> 00:13:54,190
I've never seen such love
in a pair of eyes.

151
00:13:54,300 --> 00:13:55,961
She was--

152
00:14:28,067 --> 00:14:29,898
Nothing should reveal the body...

153
00:14:31,871 --> 00:14:33,395
but the body.

154
00:14:35,307 --> 00:14:36,433
Didn't you say?

155
00:14:46,819 --> 00:14:50,448
There has to be a first time
for everything, Oscar...

156
00:14:53,092 --> 00:14:55,253
even for you.

157
00:15:03,636 --> 00:15:07,037
<i>Hush. There's
a good little fellow.</i>

158
00:15:07,172 --> 00:15:09,834
Come on. Come on, now. There.

159
00:15:11,443 --> 00:15:14,674
Now, come on, Cyril.
It's time for your bath.

160
00:15:14,780 --> 00:15:17,840
Be a good boy.
Don't make such a fuss!

161
00:15:19,785 --> 00:15:21,878
You've got to get undressed.
Come on.

162
00:15:22,821 --> 00:15:24,550
I know you hate it.

163
00:15:24,723 --> 00:15:27,624
Boys, Mrs. Wilde,
they never do what they're told.

164
00:15:27,793 --> 00:15:31,058
Oh, we're going to have
a girl next time.

165
00:15:31,163 --> 00:15:33,688
- Aren't we, Oscar?
- I must go.

166
00:15:37,069 --> 00:15:39,731
Good night, my dear.
Now you behave, Cyril.

167
00:15:39,939 --> 00:15:42,567
Remember, a gentleman should take
a bath at least once a year.

168
00:15:44,310 --> 00:15:46,301
- Good night.
- Come on, Cyril.

169
00:15:46,412 --> 00:15:47,845
It's not that bad.

170
00:15:47,980 --> 00:15:51,347
I shan't be back till late.
I'm dining with the Asquiths.

171
00:15:51,483 --> 00:15:52,848
Hush now.

172
00:15:52,985 --> 00:15:55,112
Come on, now.

173
00:16:32,925 --> 00:16:34,449
Do you love me?

174
00:16:36,862 --> 00:16:38,693
I feel...

175
00:16:38,864 --> 00:16:41,162
like a city that's been...

176
00:16:41,266 --> 00:16:43,632
under siege for 20 years.

177
00:16:45,304 --> 00:16:47,898
Suddenly the gates are thrown open...

178
00:16:48,040 --> 00:16:51,635
and the citizens come pouring out...

179
00:16:53,579 --> 00:16:55,877
to breathe the air
and walk the fields...

180
00:16:56,015 --> 00:16:58,711
and pluck the wildflowers.

181
00:17:00,486 --> 00:17:01,851
I feel...

182
00:17:03,055 --> 00:17:04,488
relieved.

183
00:17:07,893 --> 00:17:09,884
You don't worry about Constance?

184
00:17:12,131 --> 00:17:14,395
<i>''Every afternoon,
on their way home from school...</i>

185
00:17:14,500 --> 00:17:17,025
<i>the children used to play
in the garden of the selfish giant. ''</i>

186
00:17:17,169 --> 00:17:19,399
Is that the garden where we play?

187
00:17:19,505 --> 00:17:23,236
No, this is much larger and lovelier
than that, with soft green grass.

188
00:17:24,143 --> 00:17:25,804
There's grass where we go.

189
00:17:25,978 --> 00:17:29,505
Yes, but are there 1 2 peach trees
that burst into delicate blossoms...

190
00:17:29,648 --> 00:17:32,708
of pink and pearl every springtime
and bear rich fruit in the autumn?

191
00:17:32,818 --> 00:17:34,183
Are there, Mama?

192
00:17:34,319 --> 00:17:37,516
I don't think there are,
Cyril, no.

193
00:17:37,623 --> 00:17:41,286
Would you hand me a matchstick,
and I'll put this hussar's head back on?

194
00:17:41,460 --> 00:17:42,984
Thank you.

195
00:17:47,866 --> 00:17:50,528
''The birds sat on the trees
and sang so sweetly...

196
00:17:50,702 --> 00:17:53,034
that the children used
to stop their games to listen.

197
00:17:53,172 --> 00:17:55,606
'How happy we are here,'
they said to each other.''

198
00:17:55,741 --> 00:17:58,301
I don't know how they could be happy
if there was a giant.

199
00:17:58,444 --> 00:18:01,436
There wasn't, you see, not yet.
He was away, visiting a friend.

200
00:18:02,514 --> 00:18:03,879
You're always away.

201
00:18:05,717 --> 00:18:09,084
Yes, but I only go for a night or two
at a time, and I always come back.

202
00:18:09,221 --> 00:18:11,655
Whereas this giant,
the one whose garden it was...

203
00:18:11,790 --> 00:18:14,691
he'd been away for seven years,
staying with an ogre in Cornwall.

204
00:18:14,860 --> 00:18:17,420
''And after seven years,
when he'd said all he had to say...

205
00:18:17,563 --> 00:18:20,191
because his conversation
was very limited...

206
00:18:21,366 --> 00:18:24,028
he decided to return home
to his own castle.

207
00:18:24,203 --> 00:18:28,003
When he found the children playing
in his garden, he was very angry.

208
00:18:28,173 --> 00:18:30,801
'What are you doing here?' he cried.

209
00:18:30,976 --> 00:18:33,274
And all the children ran away.

210
00:18:33,412 --> 00:18:35,539
'My own garden...

211
00:18:35,647 --> 00:18:38,514
is my own garden!'
said the giant.

212
00:18:38,684 --> 00:18:41,881
'And I won't allow anyone
to play in it except myself.'

213
00:18:41,987 --> 00:18:44,547
So he built a high wall
all around...

214
00:18:44,690 --> 00:18:47,887
put up a large notice board on which
was written, in capital letters:

215
00:18:47,993 --> 00:18:50,154
'Trespassers will be prosecuted.'''

216
00:18:52,764 --> 00:18:55,665
Arthur, you're trespassing.
Cyril will now eat you.

217
00:18:55,834 --> 00:18:58,064
It's Mr. Ross, sir, with Mr. Gray.

218
00:18:58,170 --> 00:18:59,899
Heavens, I must fly.

219
00:19:00,072 --> 00:19:02,836
The horses of Apollo are pawing
impatiently at the gates.

220
00:19:03,008 --> 00:19:04,475
I beg your pardon?

221
00:19:04,610 --> 00:19:06,202
Papa must go.

222
00:19:09,715 --> 00:19:12,343
You will come back
and finish the story?

223
00:19:12,518 --> 00:19:14,611
Of course I will.

224
00:19:14,720 --> 00:19:16,551
Come on, Cyril.
It's almost teatime.

225
00:19:18,590 --> 00:19:21,423
I really don't know why people bother
painting portraits anymore.

226
00:19:21,593 --> 00:19:24,426
You can get a much better likeness
with a photograph.

227
00:19:25,931 --> 00:19:28,092
A photograph's just
one moment in time...

228
00:19:28,200 --> 00:19:30,634
one gesture, one turn of the head.

229
00:19:30,769 --> 00:19:34,034
Yes, portraits are not
likenesses, Mr. Gray.

230
00:19:34,173 --> 00:19:37,267
Painters show the soul
of the subject, the essence.

231
00:19:37,376 --> 00:19:39,708
The essence of the sitter's
vanity, you mean.

232
00:19:39,845 --> 00:19:41,312
Well...

233
00:19:41,446 --> 00:19:44,904
this is a portrait
of Lady Battersby as a young woman.

234
00:19:46,485 --> 00:19:49,648
She's over there,
as a matter of fact.

235
00:19:49,755 --> 00:19:51,620
I must go and console her.

236
00:19:58,063 --> 00:19:59,587
How nice to see you.

237
00:20:00,465 --> 00:20:02,524
Poor thing.

238
00:20:02,634 --> 00:20:04,261
I expect in her heart...

239
00:20:04,436 --> 00:20:06,700
she thinks she still
looks like this.

240
00:20:06,805 --> 00:20:09,069
If we could look young
and innocent forever--

241
00:20:09,208 --> 00:20:10,835
Do you think we'd want to?

242
00:20:12,110 --> 00:20:14,203
If our souls were ugly, yes.

243
00:20:14,313 --> 00:20:17,339
Give a man a mask,
and he'll tell you the truth.

244
00:20:20,786 --> 00:20:23,846
Have we had enough of this?
Shall we go and have dinner somewhere?

245
00:21:03,629 --> 00:21:07,224
<i>Dorian Gray is the most
wonderful book I've ever read.</i>

246
00:21:07,399 --> 00:21:09,765
<i>And the end,
when the servants break in...</i>

247
00:21:09,901 --> 00:21:13,029
and they find him wizened,
old and dead...

248
00:21:13,138 --> 00:21:14,969
and the picture young again--

249
00:21:16,174 --> 00:21:18,165
I fainted.

250
00:21:18,277 --> 00:21:20,575
My family say it's dull and wicked.

251
00:21:20,679 --> 00:21:22,044
Dull?

252
00:21:30,522 --> 00:21:32,012
It's sublime.

253
00:21:33,592 --> 00:21:37,084
It's about the masks
we wear as faces...

254
00:21:38,330 --> 00:21:40,924
and the faces we wear as masks.

255
00:21:43,602 --> 00:21:46,196
That my son should have written
a work of such--

256
00:21:46,338 --> 00:21:49,501
People say it's full
of dangerous paradoxes.

257
00:21:50,776 --> 00:21:54,007
Hardly anyone will speak
to us anymore.

258
00:21:54,112 --> 00:21:55,773
We're ceasing to be respectable.

259
00:21:59,618 --> 00:22:03,213
Artists care nothing
about respectability.

260
00:22:04,623 --> 00:22:06,750
It's only jealousy.

261
00:22:06,858 --> 00:22:11,420
It's the spite of the untalented
for the men of genius.

262
00:22:14,066 --> 00:22:15,431
Where is Oscar?

263
00:22:16,368 --> 00:22:18,666
He's in the Lake District,
writing a play.

264
00:22:19,638 --> 00:22:21,435
- A drama?
- A comedy.

265
00:22:23,108 --> 00:22:25,133
Robbie Ross has gone
to keep him company.

266
00:22:27,346 --> 00:22:28,836
I do like Robbie.

267
00:22:30,349 --> 00:22:31,976
And they both love you.

268
00:22:33,585 --> 00:22:35,610
Oh, it'll be a great success.

269
00:22:36,488 --> 00:22:39,719
Oscar's made for the stage.

270
00:22:53,739 --> 00:22:55,798
- Author! Author!
- Author!

271
00:23:04,449 --> 00:23:06,508
Oscar, please!

272
00:23:06,618 --> 00:23:09,212
- Magnificent!
- Well done, everybody.

273
00:23:24,603 --> 00:23:28,937
Ladies and gentlemen,
I have enjoyed this evening immensely.

274
00:23:29,074 --> 00:23:33,568
The actors have given us a charming
rendering of a delightful play...

275
00:23:33,712 --> 00:23:37,045
and your appreciation
has been most intelligent.

276
00:23:37,182 --> 00:23:40,345
I congratulate you on the great success
of your performance...

277
00:23:40,452 --> 00:23:43,751
which persuades me that you think
almost as highly of this play...

278
00:23:43,855 --> 00:23:45,686
as I do myself.

279
00:23:57,569 --> 00:24:00,333
Absolutely splendid, Oscar.
An absolute triumph!

280
00:24:00,505 --> 00:24:02,871
- Thank you so much. Thank you.
- Well done.

281
00:24:03,008 --> 00:24:04,839
How sweet of you to say so.

282
00:24:06,244 --> 00:24:08,405
It went so well, Oscar.

283
00:24:09,648 --> 00:24:11,878
Even better than I'd--

284
00:24:11,983 --> 00:24:14,543
They loved it.
They absolutely loved it.

285
00:24:14,686 --> 00:24:16,984
And I, dear boy, love you.

286
00:24:17,122 --> 00:24:18,714
Congratulations, Oscar.

287
00:24:18,857 --> 00:24:20,654
Thank you.

288
00:24:20,826 --> 00:24:22,521
It's good to see you.

289
00:24:22,694 --> 00:24:24,855
Hello.

290
00:24:25,730 --> 00:24:27,561
Mr. Wilde.
Wonderful, really wonderful.

291
00:24:27,732 --> 00:24:29,597
- Oscar.
- Sphinx!

292
00:24:29,768 --> 00:24:33,295
You really must be careful.
You're in grave danger of becoming rich.

293
00:24:35,273 --> 00:24:38,800
- It was wonderful. I knew it would be.
- Thank you, Robbie.

294
00:24:38,944 --> 00:24:41,469
Everyone's dying to know
who the real Lady Windermere is.

295
00:24:41,613 --> 00:24:44,343
The real Lady Windermere is every woman
in this room, and most of the men.

296
00:24:44,516 --> 00:24:45,881
- Oscar!
- Lionel!

297
00:24:46,017 --> 00:24:48,178
It's a wonderful play.

298
00:24:48,286 --> 00:24:50,117
My cousin Lord Alfred Douglas
is here.

299
00:24:50,288 --> 00:24:52,950
He would like very much
to congratulate you.

300
00:25:04,870 --> 00:25:07,338
- Wonderful.
- Oscar, this is Bosie Douglas.

301
00:25:07,506 --> 00:25:11,670
We met last year.
Lionel brought me to tea at Tite Street.

302
00:25:11,776 --> 00:25:13,607
How could I possibly forget?

303
00:25:17,315 --> 00:25:19,146
I love your play.

304
00:25:19,317 --> 00:25:21,342
The audience didn't know
whether you meant your jokes or not.

305
00:25:21,453 --> 00:25:23,250
You shocked them...

306
00:25:23,421 --> 00:25:26,015
especially with your speech.

307
00:25:26,191 --> 00:25:29,490
But the more frivolous you seem,
the more serious you are, aren't you?

308
00:25:29,594 --> 00:25:31,892
- I love that.
- Thank you.

309
00:25:31,997 --> 00:25:34,295
I always say,
the young are the only critics...

310
00:25:34,432 --> 00:25:36,457
with enough experience
to judge my work.

311
00:25:36,568 --> 00:25:39,128
- Splendid, Oscar.
- We need shocking.

312
00:25:39,271 --> 00:25:42,104
People are so banal.
And you use your wit like a foil.

313
00:25:42,274 --> 00:25:46,108
You cut through all those
starched shirt fronts.

314
00:25:46,278 --> 00:25:49,406
You draw blood.
It's magnificent.

315
00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:52,642
I wish you'd draw some blood
down in Oxford...

316
00:25:52,751 --> 00:25:54,275
though you'd need a miracle.

317
00:25:54,419 --> 00:25:56,785
All the dons at my college
have dust in their veins.

318
00:25:56,922 --> 00:26:00,619
At which college
do you educate the fellows?

319
00:26:00,792 --> 00:26:02,282
Magdalen.

320
00:26:02,427 --> 00:26:04,019
My own college.

321
00:26:04,162 --> 00:26:07,723
I shall claim the privilege of
a graduate and take tutorials with you.

322
00:26:09,100 --> 00:26:12,433
Come soon, then.
They're threatening to send me down.

323
00:26:12,571 --> 00:26:15,699
How could they be so cruel
to one so beautiful?

324
00:26:21,680 --> 00:26:24,740
Dons-- they're so middle class.

325
00:26:24,849 --> 00:26:28,512
Oscar, you've shocked the whole
of London, smoking on stage like that.

326
00:26:28,687 --> 00:26:30,746
Excellent.
Then we shall run for a year.

327
00:26:30,855 --> 00:26:33,221
Oscar, you must say something
to Marion Terry.

328
00:26:33,358 --> 00:26:34,882
She was good, wasn't she?

329
00:26:35,026 --> 00:26:38,052
So good, I think she wrote
most of the lines herself.

330
00:26:38,163 --> 00:26:40,723
- Excuse me, Lord Alfred.
- Bosie, please.

331
00:26:47,005 --> 00:26:49,530
- You must be so thrilled, Oscar.
- I know.

332
00:26:49,674 --> 00:26:51,665
Isn't it humiliating?

333
00:26:51,776 --> 00:26:55,940
<i>'' 'My own garden is my own garden, '
said the giant.</i>

334
00:26:56,047 --> 00:26:59,448
So he built a high wall
all round it...

335
00:26:59,618 --> 00:27:01,483
and put up a notice board:

336
00:27:01,653 --> 00:27:04,918
'Trespassers will be prosecuted.'

337
00:27:05,023 --> 00:27:08,322
He was a very selfish giant.

338
00:27:08,426 --> 00:27:11,589
The poor children
had now nowhere to play.

339
00:27:11,696 --> 00:27:13,527
They tried to play on the road...

340
00:27:13,698 --> 00:27:17,566
but the road was very dusty and full of
hard stones, and they did not like it.

341
00:27:17,736 --> 00:27:20,432
They used to wander round the high wall
when their lessons were over...

342
00:27:20,639 --> 00:27:24,370
<i>and talk about
the beautiful garden inside.</i>

343
00:27:24,542 --> 00:27:28,706
<i>'How happy we were there, '
they said to each other. ''</i>

344
00:27:28,813 --> 00:27:32,271
I hope he was
a very beautiful boy.

345
00:27:32,417 --> 00:27:36,786
Well, pretty, you know,
in a street-Arab sort of way.

346
00:27:36,921 --> 00:27:39,583
There's no point being blackmailed
by an ugly one.

347
00:27:45,964 --> 00:27:49,832
What's tiresome is he's threatened
to show my letters to my father.

348
00:27:50,001 --> 00:27:54,267
Who will show them to all his friends
for the excellence of their style.

349
00:27:55,874 --> 00:27:58,434
You don't know him.
He's a brute.

350
00:27:59,744 --> 00:28:03,339
Really. He carries a whip
wherever he goes.

351
00:28:06,117 --> 00:28:07,948
He used to beat my mother.

352
00:28:09,320 --> 00:28:12,153
He beat my brothers.
He thrashed me from the age--

353
00:28:12,323 --> 00:28:14,450
My dear boy.

354
00:28:16,795 --> 00:28:19,787
Of course, he's
practically illiterate.

355
00:28:20,965 --> 00:28:23,263
He probably won't understand
the letters anyway.

356
00:28:23,401 --> 00:28:25,995
By an unforgivable oversight,
I've never been blackmailed myself...

357
00:28:26,171 --> 00:28:29,629
but my friends assure me that
a hundred pounds will usually suffice.

358
00:28:29,774 --> 00:28:31,139
Really?

359
00:28:31,276 --> 00:28:33,471
God, I-- You promise?

360
00:28:33,578 --> 00:28:37,207
Leave it to Lewis--
George Lewis-- my solicitor.

361
00:28:37,382 --> 00:28:40,715
He knows what he's doing.
He acts for the Prince of Wales.

362
00:28:49,127 --> 00:28:51,425
<i>Leave me not to pine</i>

363
00:28:51,529 --> 00:28:56,592
<i>Alone and desolate</i>

364
00:28:56,735 --> 00:29:01,001
<i>No fate seem fair as mine</i>

365
00:29:01,139 --> 00:29:05,337
<i>No happiness</i>

366
00:29:05,443 --> 00:29:07,206
<i>So great</i>

367
00:29:07,378 --> 00:29:09,141
Isn't he killing, Mr. Wilde?

368
00:29:09,314 --> 00:29:12,010
<i>- And nature day by day
- He's perfect.</i>

369
00:29:12,183 --> 00:29:15,175
He's perfect in every way.

370
00:29:15,286 --> 00:29:19,188
<i>In accents clear</i>

371
00:29:19,357 --> 00:29:23,919
<i>This joyous roundelay</i>

372
00:29:24,896 --> 00:29:28,354
<i>He loves me</i>

373
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:30,661
<i>He is here</i>

374
00:29:38,443 --> 00:29:42,777
<i>He loves me</i>

375
00:29:42,914 --> 00:29:45,576
<i>He is here</i>

376
00:29:56,928 --> 00:29:58,987
That was lovely. Well done, Bosie.

377
00:29:59,097 --> 00:30:00,689
Yes, absolutely enchanting.

378
00:30:00,865 --> 00:30:02,298
More tea, anyone?

379
00:31:27,986 --> 00:31:31,046
I don't want to sit here.
I want to sit there.

380
00:31:31,155 --> 00:31:33,146
You heard what Lord Alfred said.

381
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:37,387
I want everyone to look at us.

382
00:31:37,495 --> 00:31:41,329
I want everyone to say, ''Look,
there's Oscar Wilde with his boy.''

383
00:31:50,108 --> 00:31:53,168
So, what shall we let people
see us eating?

384
00:31:54,512 --> 00:31:57,743
Fois gras and lobster
and champagne.

385
00:31:57,849 --> 00:32:00,511
For two.
We do everything together.

386
00:32:00,685 --> 00:32:02,243
Very good, Mr. Wilde.

387
00:32:10,161 --> 00:32:13,722
I think he enjoyed thrashing me.

388
00:32:13,865 --> 00:32:15,628
All my family are mad.

389
00:32:17,735 --> 00:32:21,796
My uncle slit his throat last year
in a railway hotel.

390
00:32:21,940 --> 00:32:23,271
Which station?

391
00:32:24,943 --> 00:32:26,274
Euston.

392
00:32:28,479 --> 00:32:31,642
All life's really serious journeys
involve a railway terminus.

393
00:32:34,085 --> 00:32:36,451
And now I must go
to the station myself.

394
00:32:37,956 --> 00:32:41,289
Sarah Bernhardt thinks she knows
better than I do how to play Salome.

395
00:32:41,426 --> 00:32:42,415
Stay.

396
00:32:44,529 --> 00:32:45,962
Please stay.

397
00:32:48,099 --> 00:32:50,624
At least till this evening.

398
00:32:52,904 --> 00:32:54,735
Sarah is divine, as you are.

399
00:32:56,341 --> 00:33:00,334
She will be wonderful at the play's
climax when Salome kisses the lips...

400
00:33:00,445 --> 00:33:02,879
of the severed head
ofJohn the Baptist.

401
00:33:03,014 --> 00:33:06,450
''Ah, thou wouldst not suffer me
to kiss thy mouth,Jokanaan.''

402
00:33:06,584 --> 00:33:09,451
Jokanaan is
an old Hebrew name forJohn.

403
00:33:09,620 --> 00:33:11,918
''Well, I will kiss it now.

404
00:33:12,056 --> 00:33:14,786
I will bite it with my teeth
as one bites a ripe fruit.

405
00:33:14,993 --> 00:33:18,292
Yes, I will kiss
thy mouth,Jokanaan.

406
00:33:19,998 --> 00:33:23,490
Thy body is white like the snows
that lie on the mountains...

407
00:33:24,635 --> 00:33:27,399
<i>like the snows that lie
on the mountains ofJudea...</i>

408
00:33:27,572 --> 00:33:30,370
<i>and come down into the valleys.</i>

409
00:33:30,541 --> 00:33:32,839
<i>The roses in the garden
of the queen of Arabia...</i>

410
00:33:32,944 --> 00:33:35,174
<i>are not so white as thy body. ''</i>

411
00:33:43,488 --> 00:33:45,752
<i>I'm not good enough
for him anymore.</i>

412
00:33:48,326 --> 00:33:50,556
I'm just the son
of a carpenter, while Bosie--

413
00:33:50,661 --> 00:33:53,528
Oscar's only ever
been smitten before.

414
00:33:55,500 --> 00:33:58,958
He was smitten with me.
He was smitten with you.

415
00:33:59,103 --> 00:34:01,128
I wasn't smitten.

416
00:34:06,477 --> 00:34:07,842
I loved him.

417
00:34:07,979 --> 00:34:12,473
Well, now he's fallen in love.

418
00:34:13,651 --> 00:34:15,949
I'm halfway to hellfire.
I'm not joking.

419
00:34:18,189 --> 00:34:20,020
Someone else was
a carpenter's son.

420
00:34:23,061 --> 00:34:25,086
I've given in
and become a Catholic.

421
00:34:26,964 --> 00:34:29,558
I find confession...

422
00:34:29,734 --> 00:34:31,201
wonderfully consoling.

423
00:34:31,335 --> 00:34:32,859
I can't go to confession...

424
00:34:34,338 --> 00:34:36,169
when I want to kill Bosie...

425
00:34:39,444 --> 00:34:41,173
or myself.

426
00:34:49,387 --> 00:34:52,151
- Oscar's furious.
- He has no right to be.

427
00:34:52,323 --> 00:34:54,917
He knew perfectly well the Lord
Chamberlain would never allow...

428
00:34:55,093 --> 00:34:56,890
a play with biblical characters.

429
00:34:57,095 --> 00:34:59,586
Oscar doesn't think there should be
censorship of plays at all.

430
00:34:59,730 --> 00:35:01,721
Of course there
must be censorship.

431
00:35:01,833 --> 00:35:05,200
Or people would say what they meant,
and then where should we be?

432
00:35:05,336 --> 00:35:07,804
- When is he coming to join us?
- He's not.

433
00:35:07,939 --> 00:35:10,032
He must stay
and look after Lord Alfred.

434
00:35:10,141 --> 00:35:13,372
Those Douglases are always ill,
when they're not demented.

435
00:35:13,478 --> 00:35:15,742
One of them roasted
a kitchen boy on a spit.

436
00:35:15,847 --> 00:35:18,247
And Bosie's father,
Lord Queensberry--

437
00:35:18,382 --> 00:35:20,850
he's a dreadful man, Constance--

438
00:35:20,985 --> 00:35:23,510
eoesn't believe in God
or marriage.

439
00:35:23,654 --> 00:35:26,088
A marquis should set
a proper example...

440
00:35:26,224 --> 00:35:29,318
or what are the upper classes for?

441
00:35:29,427 --> 00:35:31,224
I tell you...

442
00:35:31,395 --> 00:35:34,990
I wouldn't want a daughter of mine
to marry a Douglas.

443
00:35:37,435 --> 00:35:38,959
I haven't got a daughter.

444
00:35:39,137 --> 00:35:41,401
Plenty of time still, my dear.

445
00:35:48,346 --> 00:35:49,711
I see.

446
00:35:51,249 --> 00:35:52,773
It's my fault.

447
00:35:54,352 --> 00:35:57,014
After Vyvyan was born,
all I could think of was the children.

448
00:36:00,491 --> 00:36:04,291
So that's why Oscar spends
so much time with his men friends.

449
00:36:04,462 --> 00:36:06,987
Oscar needs disciples.

450
00:36:07,165 --> 00:36:10,362
Lord Alfred's a poet.
A very fine poet, Oscar says.

451
00:36:10,468 --> 00:36:14,234
He's studying classics.
Oscar and he talk about Plato.

452
00:36:17,041 --> 00:36:18,406
There's nothing wrong.

453
00:36:19,710 --> 00:36:21,371
Really, there isn't.

454
00:36:21,546 --> 00:36:23,741
It's not whether
there is anything wrong.

455
00:36:23,848 --> 00:36:26,646
It's whether or not
there appears to be.

456
00:36:26,817 --> 00:36:28,648
That's all people care about.

457
00:36:28,819 --> 00:36:32,585
The empire was not built
by men like Bosie Douglas.

458
00:36:34,625 --> 00:36:36,149
<i>''Then the spring came...</i>

459
00:36:38,062 --> 00:36:41,589
<i>only in the garden of the selfish giant
it was still winter.</i>

460
00:36:41,732 --> 00:36:44,724
<i>The birds did not care to sing in it,
as there were no children.</i>

461
00:36:44,835 --> 00:36:47,303
<i>And the trees forgot to blossom.</i>

462
00:36:47,438 --> 00:36:50,532
<i>The snow covered up the grass
with her great white cloak...</i>

463
00:36:50,641 --> 00:36:54,372
<i>and the frost painted
all the trees silver. ''</i>

464
00:37:47,131 --> 00:37:48,689
Let's go out.

465
00:37:48,833 --> 00:37:50,198
If you like.

466
00:37:55,273 --> 00:37:58,606
The thing about renters is you
don't have to consider their feelings.

467
00:37:58,743 --> 00:38:01,974
But if someone is willing to give one
pleasure, one should show gratitude.

468
00:38:02,079 --> 00:38:04,104
No. Money, that's all they want.

469
00:38:05,316 --> 00:38:09,616
What's wonderful about going
to Taylor's is no one pretends.

470
00:38:09,720 --> 00:38:11,551
You just do it
and be done with it.

471
00:38:19,730 --> 00:38:21,254
I do love you, Oscar.

472
00:38:23,634 --> 00:38:26,159
But variety is
the spice of life.

473
00:38:30,241 --> 00:38:32,072
You can watch me, if you like.

474
00:38:34,445 --> 00:38:36,811
<i>You must attempt to keep a grasp
upon your sobriety.</i>

475
00:38:38,516 --> 00:38:42,043
That is disgusting.
We'll have less of that.

476
00:38:42,186 --> 00:38:44,484
- Good evening.
- Lord Alfred.

477
00:38:44,588 --> 00:38:46,249
Alfred Taylor, this is Oscar.

478
00:38:46,424 --> 00:38:49,086
Delighted to make
your acquaintance, Oscar.

479
00:38:49,260 --> 00:38:51,057
Charles Parker. I remember you.

480
00:38:52,330 --> 00:38:53,524
Hello, Oscar.

481
00:38:54,865 --> 00:38:56,594
Charming to see you again.

482
00:39:01,806 --> 00:39:03,671
- Do you smoke?
- I do everything.

483
00:39:03,841 --> 00:39:07,004
- Yeah, everything that pays.
- Expertly, I might add.

484
00:39:10,181 --> 00:39:11,876
Mr. Wilde, some wine.

485
00:39:12,049 --> 00:39:13,880
Thank you.

486
00:39:14,051 --> 00:39:17,179
- It's a nice case.
- I want you to keep it.

487
00:39:20,024 --> 00:39:22,288
Thank you.

488
00:39:22,393 --> 00:39:26,659
So, this is a den of vice.
I should call it more of a garden.

489
00:39:26,764 --> 00:39:29,028
Such pretty flowers, Mr. Taylor.

490
00:39:29,133 --> 00:39:31,624
How wise of you to keep
the curtains closed.

491
00:39:31,769 --> 00:39:33,600
They would never grow
in the common light of day.

492
00:39:33,771 --> 00:39:36,604
- Who are you calling common?
- Certainly not you, dear boy.

493
00:39:36,774 --> 00:39:39,902
You seem to be a flower
of the rarest hue.

494
00:39:49,086 --> 00:39:52,681
Bosie never told me that you
were a botanist, Mr. Taylor...

495
00:39:52,857 --> 00:39:55,917
that you roam the earth, climbing
the highest peaks of the Himalayas...

496
00:39:56,026 --> 00:39:58,221
and plunging
into the darkest forests...

497
00:39:58,329 --> 00:40:01,321
of Borneo to return triumphant...

498
00:40:01,432 --> 00:40:04,299
to this delightful conservatory
in the shadow of Westminster Abbey...

499
00:40:04,468 --> 00:40:06,368
to exhibit your specimens.

500
00:40:07,471 --> 00:40:09,302
The boys are all Londoners, actually.

501
00:40:10,641 --> 00:40:13,075
Impossible.
I see Londoners every day...

502
00:40:13,210 --> 00:40:16,646
but never such
exotic blooms as these.

503
00:40:16,781 --> 00:40:18,908
Does he always talk like this?

504
00:40:19,016 --> 00:40:21,007
Not when he's in bed.

505
00:40:31,195 --> 00:40:32,856
<i>I am discreet.</i>

506
00:40:33,030 --> 00:40:36,864
<i>Bosie is far too grand for that.
He wants everyone to know.</i>

507
00:40:38,035 --> 00:40:40,868
- You must understand--
- I must be with young people, Robbie.

508
00:40:41,038 --> 00:40:43,563
They're so frank and free.

509
00:40:43,707 --> 00:40:45,538
They make me feel young myself.

510
00:40:45,709 --> 00:40:47,973
That's all very well,
but what would you say...

511
00:40:48,078 --> 00:40:50,911
if someone wanted
to go to bed with your son?

512
00:40:51,081 --> 00:40:52,446
Cyril's eight.

513
00:40:52,583 --> 00:40:54,915
What will you say when he's 1 8?

514
00:40:58,355 --> 00:41:01,847
Nothing. He must do
as his nature dictates...

515
00:41:01,992 --> 00:41:04,586
<i>as I only wish I had done.</i>

516
00:41:04,762 --> 00:41:08,289
'''I do believe the spring has come
at last,' said the giant.

517
00:41:08,466 --> 00:41:11,264
He jumped out of bed,
and looked out of the window.''

518
00:41:11,469 --> 00:41:13,767
- What did he see?
- You tell me.

519
00:41:13,904 --> 00:41:15,428
No, you tell it.

520
00:41:15,573 --> 00:41:19,600
All right.
''He saw the most wonderful sight.

521
00:41:19,710 --> 00:41:21,735
Through a little hole
in the wall...

522
00:41:21,846 --> 00:41:24,314
the children had crept back
into the garden and were sitting...

523
00:41:24,482 --> 00:41:26,279
on the branches of the trees.

524
00:41:26,484 --> 00:41:29,647
And every tree that he could see,
there was a little child.

525
00:41:29,753 --> 00:41:31,584
The trees were so glad that they--''

526
00:41:31,755 --> 00:41:33,416
They covered themselves
with blossoms!

527
00:41:33,591 --> 00:41:34,888
Blossoms!

528
00:41:35,025 --> 00:41:38,620
''And were waving their arms gently
above the children's heads.

529
00:41:38,762 --> 00:41:42,425
And the birds were twittering
and singing above them with delight.

530
00:41:42,600 --> 00:41:46,434
And the flowers were looking up
through the grass and laughing.

531
00:41:46,604 --> 00:41:50,631
Oscar, it's time the boys changed,
or we'll miss the train.

532
00:41:50,741 --> 00:41:52,641
Come on, boys.

533
00:41:52,810 --> 00:41:55,040
Papa, can't we stay?

534
00:41:55,145 --> 00:41:58,808
Papa's got to work.
He's got to finish his play.

535
00:41:58,983 --> 00:42:00,507
Yes, poor dear Papa.

536
00:42:00,651 --> 00:42:02,812
Poor Papa.

537
00:42:02,920 --> 00:42:07,152
Poor, poor, poor, poor, poor Papa.

538
00:42:09,593 --> 00:42:11,788
<i>Where is Oscar?
We haven't seen him at all.</i>

539
00:42:11,896 --> 00:42:14,797
Where do you think he is? He's working.
He is a writer, after all.

540
00:42:14,965 --> 00:42:17,627
I hear your father's threatening
to shoot Lord Roseberry.

541
00:42:17,801 --> 00:42:21,464
Really? He usually
prefers the horsewhip.

542
00:42:21,639 --> 00:42:23,766
Says he's been buggering
your brother.

543
00:42:23,874 --> 00:42:26,707
Well, Roseberry is Secretary of State
for Foreign Affairs...

544
00:42:26,877 --> 00:42:29,345
and Francis is
his private secretary.

545
00:42:29,480 --> 00:42:31,914
Actually, Francis is
about to get engaged.

546
00:42:32,049 --> 00:42:35,348
What's your father
talking about, then?

547
00:42:36,654 --> 00:42:38,713
He's obsessed with sex.

548
00:42:38,822 --> 00:42:40,687
He thinks Oscar's buggering me...

549
00:42:40,858 --> 00:42:43,554
as though I'd allow
anyone to do that.

550
00:42:55,372 --> 00:42:56,896
I'm sick of the country.

551
00:43:00,878 --> 00:43:02,402
Let's get back to London.

552
00:43:08,586 --> 00:43:11,350
What's the point of us living together
if you're always working?

553
00:43:11,522 --> 00:43:15,014
- I have responsibilities-- a family.
- God, not that again!

554
00:43:17,595 --> 00:43:20,689
I ask my friends over from Oxford,
and you just disappear.

555
00:43:25,469 --> 00:43:28,097
I'd be better off
staying at my mother's.

556
00:43:28,272 --> 00:43:31,469
- At least she's there.
- You asked me to take this house--

557
00:43:31,609 --> 00:43:33,167
Now I'm bored with it.

558
00:43:33,310 --> 00:43:36,871
- And with you.
- I can't give it up.

559
00:43:37,014 --> 00:43:40,381
It's paid for in advance.
Until I finish my new--

560
00:43:42,019 --> 00:43:43,384
Bosie, dear...

561
00:43:43,520 --> 00:43:45,784
you have beauty,
you have breeding...

562
00:43:45,889 --> 00:43:48,449
and, most glorious of all,
you have youth.

563
00:43:48,626 --> 00:43:51,117
But you are very fantastical
if you think that pleasures...

564
00:43:51,261 --> 00:43:53,786
don't have to be earned
and paid for.

565
00:43:53,931 --> 00:43:57,765
Whenever I want to do anything,
you say you can't afford it...

566
00:43:57,935 --> 00:44:00,233
but you give all those renters
cigarette cases.

567
00:44:00,371 --> 00:44:02,498
But I've lavished presents on you!

568
00:44:02,640 --> 00:44:05,370
Every penny I've earned from my play
I have spent on you!

569
00:44:05,542 --> 00:44:08,170
I'm sure you've been counting.

570
00:44:08,345 --> 00:44:11,473
You're so mean
and penny-pinching...

571
00:44:11,582 --> 00:44:14,142
and middle-class, all you can
think about is your bank balance.

572
00:44:14,284 --> 00:44:16,275
For God's sake!
This is intolerable!

573
00:44:16,387 --> 00:44:20,915
No gentleman ever has the slightest idea
what his bank balance is!

574
00:44:22,526 --> 00:44:24,118
You're absurd!

575
00:44:24,294 --> 00:44:26,558
Telling everyone
how they ought to live.

576
00:44:26,664 --> 00:44:29,292
You're so vulgar!

577
00:44:29,466 --> 00:44:31,991
I never want
to see you again, ever.

578
00:44:32,136 --> 00:44:35,697
All right, then.
If that's what you want, then you go!

579
00:44:35,839 --> 00:44:37,431
Get out!

580
00:44:41,245 --> 00:44:43,679
<i>''But in the farthest corner
of the garden...</i>

581
00:44:43,814 --> 00:44:48,114
<i>it was still winter, and in it
was standing a little boy.</i>

582
00:44:48,252 --> 00:44:52,484
<i>He was so small, he could not reach up
to the branches of the tree.</i>

583
00:44:52,589 --> 00:44:55,490
<i>'Climb up, little boy, '
said the tree.</i>

584
00:44:55,693 --> 00:44:58,992
<i>But the little boy was too tiny. ''</i>

585
00:44:59,129 --> 00:45:01,791
Egypt is lovely this time of year.

586
00:45:01,965 --> 00:45:05,264
- But you mustn't idle your time away.
- Mother.

587
00:45:05,402 --> 00:45:08,235
And I want you
to promise me something:

588
00:45:09,940 --> 00:45:12,067
not to write to Oscar Wilde.

589
00:45:13,510 --> 00:45:15,740
I can't do that.
I love Oscar.

590
00:45:17,514 --> 00:45:20,108
I love him as a disciple
loves his teacher.

591
00:45:20,250 --> 00:45:22,514
But he's not fit to teach anything.
He's evil.

592
00:45:23,787 --> 00:45:26,255
Do you really think your own son
could love someone evil?

593
00:45:28,025 --> 00:45:31,392
I just wish I could love Oscar
as loyally, devotedly...

594
00:45:31,528 --> 00:45:34,258
unselfishly and purely
as he loves me.

595
00:45:37,067 --> 00:45:39,661
But I'm not as good as he is.

596
00:45:41,672 --> 00:45:43,401
I probably never will be.

597
00:45:46,043 --> 00:45:47,908
Good-bye, then.

598
00:46:03,227 --> 00:46:05,252
<i>''I adore simple pleasures.</i>

599
00:46:05,362 --> 00:46:08,126
<i>They are the last refuge
of the complex.</i>

600
00:46:08,298 --> 00:46:10,732
But, if you wish,
let us stay here.

601
00:46:10,868 --> 00:46:12,768
Yes, let us stay here.

602
00:46:12,936 --> 00:46:16,394
<i>The Book of Life begins
with a man and a woman in a garden.''</i>

603
00:46:16,540 --> 00:46:18,371
''It ends with 'Revelations.'''

604
00:46:18,542 --> 00:46:21,170
Yes. Mr. Tree, may I?

605
00:46:21,345 --> 00:46:23,870
I'm delighted, of course,
that you find my lines funny...

606
00:46:24,014 --> 00:46:26,414
but please don't try and make
the audience laugh with them.

607
00:46:26,550 --> 00:46:29,212
They should sound completely
spontaneous and natural...

608
00:46:29,386 --> 00:46:31,479
as though people spoke
like that all the time.

609
00:46:31,588 --> 00:46:33,920
Yes, of course.

610
00:46:34,057 --> 00:46:35,422
Let's try again.

611
00:46:37,194 --> 00:46:39,662
You should break with Bosie
more often, Oscar.

612
00:46:39,797 --> 00:46:44,063
Then we'd have more of
your spontaneous and natural plays.

613
00:46:44,168 --> 00:46:47,069
Bosie was envious.
That's why he stopped Oscar working.

614
00:46:47,237 --> 00:46:49,467
- That's not true.
- Of course it is.

615
00:46:49,573 --> 00:46:52,633
His poems aren't nearly
as good as you pretend...

616
00:46:52,743 --> 00:46:54,233
and he knows it.

617
00:46:54,378 --> 00:46:57,279
- He's just a shallow little--
- Rivulet.

618
00:46:59,883 --> 00:47:03,341
Bosie's a child, a vulnerable child.
He needs love.

619
00:47:03,487 --> 00:47:05,216
We all need love.

620
00:47:06,423 --> 00:47:08,482
But which of us can give it?

621
00:47:08,592 --> 00:47:11,254
<i>Wish you a merry Christmas</i>

622
00:47:11,428 --> 00:47:13,862
<i>We wish you a merry Christmas</i>

623
00:47:16,667 --> 00:47:19,101
<i>And a happy New Year</i>

624
00:47:19,236 --> 00:47:21,796
<i>Good tidings we bring</i>

625
00:47:21,939 --> 00:47:24,407
<i>To you and your kin</i>

626
00:47:24,541 --> 00:47:26,975
<i>We wish you a merry Christmas</i>

627
00:47:27,110 --> 00:47:30,477
<i>And a happy New Year</i>

628
00:47:30,614 --> 00:47:32,980
- Cracker time!
- It is cracker time.

629
00:47:33,116 --> 00:47:35,880
I won this time. Look. There.
One for you, one for me.

630
00:47:36,053 --> 00:47:39,511
<i>''And the giant's heart melted
as he looked out.</i>

631
00:47:39,656 --> 00:47:42,784
<i>'How selfish I have been, '
he said.</i>

632
00:47:42,893 --> 00:47:45,987
<i>'Now I know why the spring
would not come here.</i>

633
00:47:46,096 --> 00:47:48,690
<i>I will put that little boy
on top of the tree...</i>

634
00:47:48,866 --> 00:47:50,993
<i>and I will knock down the wall,
and my garden shall be...</i>

635
00:47:51,101 --> 00:47:53,763
<i>the children's playground
forever and ever. '</i>

636
00:47:53,937 --> 00:47:56,804
<i>He was really very sorry
for what he had done. ''</i>

637
00:47:58,108 --> 00:48:00,235
This is really nice, even though--

638
00:48:01,478 --> 00:48:05,073
<i>''So he crept downstairs and opened
the front door quite softly...</i>

639
00:48:05,215 --> 00:48:07,206
<i>and went out into the garden.</i>

640
00:48:10,921 --> 00:48:13,685
<i>that he did not see
the giant coming.</i>

641
00:48:13,891 --> 00:48:18,191
<i>And the giant stole up behind him
and took him gently by the hand...</i>

642
00:48:18,328 --> 00:48:20,387
<i>and put him up into the tree.</i>

643
00:48:20,497 --> 00:48:22,488
<i>And the tree broke
at once into blossom...</i>

644
00:48:22,599 --> 00:48:25,193
<i>and the birds came and sang on it,
and the little boy...</i>

645
00:48:25,369 --> 00:48:27,360
<i>stretched out his two arms...</i>

646
00:48:27,471 --> 00:48:29,769
<i>and flung them
round the giant's neck...</i>

647
00:48:29,907 --> 00:48:31,534
<i>and kissed him. ''</i>

648
00:49:05,042 --> 00:49:07,875
I don't care what people think.
I love you.

649
00:49:08,045 --> 00:49:11,481
It's all that matters to me.
It was agony being away from you.

650
00:49:11,615 --> 00:49:13,344
Well, here I am.

651
00:49:13,517 --> 00:49:15,781
Oh, Bosie, you're
my catastrophe, my doom.

652
00:49:15,886 --> 00:49:17,717
Everyone says so, even me.

653
00:49:19,323 --> 00:49:20,688
I missed you.

654
00:49:23,093 --> 00:49:27,086
I thought you might like something
to celebrate your return.

655
00:49:33,270 --> 00:49:36,103
When I saw them in the window,
they begged me on their knees...

656
00:49:36,273 --> 00:49:37,797
to make them yours.

657
00:49:39,443 --> 00:49:42,037
I'll put them on now.
They're superb.

658
00:49:57,828 --> 00:50:00,820
- I'll sit there. I want a proper table.
- Is there something wrong, my lord?

659
00:50:00,931 --> 00:50:03,729
This young fool wants me
to sit by the service door.

660
00:50:03,900 --> 00:50:05,800
Oh, God, my father.

661
00:50:06,003 --> 00:50:09,564
I'm extremely sorry. He's new,
and he didn't know who you were.

662
00:50:11,375 --> 00:50:13,639
Bosie, you're not going to flee.

663
00:50:19,349 --> 00:50:20,941
Give me the menu.

664
00:50:25,422 --> 00:50:27,890
I'll have the pea soup
and then the salmon.

665
00:50:28,025 --> 00:50:29,925
Will you have it with us, Papa?

666
00:50:31,895 --> 00:50:35,058
I'm lunching with Oscar Wilde.
Will you join us?

667
00:50:40,170 --> 00:50:42,468
I told you never to see
that vile cur again.

668
00:50:42,606 --> 00:50:46,098
He's not vile or a cur.
He's utterly delightful. Come and see.

669
00:50:48,678 --> 00:50:51,272
How do you know what he's like
when you've never met him?

670
00:50:52,983 --> 00:50:55,781
You're not a man to be influenced
by other people's opinions.

671
00:51:04,528 --> 00:51:08,430
Oscar, you've never met
my father, have you?

672
00:51:08,598 --> 00:51:10,031
Lord Queensberry.

673
00:51:13,403 --> 00:51:17,100
Bosie has told me so much about
your exploits on the racetrack.

674
00:51:19,142 --> 00:51:23,579
I've never heard such bad luck
as yours with the Grand National.

675
00:51:23,713 --> 00:51:25,943
Bosie tells me
that you would have won...

676
00:51:26,083 --> 00:51:28,278
but that your cousin
wouldn't let you ride the horse?

677
00:51:30,087 --> 00:51:32,112
Bloody fool said I was too old.

678
00:51:33,223 --> 00:51:35,885
Why, you're never too old.
I'd ridden Old Joe on the gallops.

679
00:51:37,394 --> 00:51:39,259
Came in at 40 to 1 .

680
00:51:39,429 --> 00:51:41,761
No horse could ever have carried me
over the jumps, I fear.

681
00:51:41,898 --> 00:51:43,263
What are you having?

682
00:51:44,568 --> 00:51:47,162
- Pea soup and salmon.
- Then I shall join you.

683
00:51:47,337 --> 00:51:49,567
Spring is the time
to lunch on salmon...

684
00:51:49,673 --> 00:51:52,107
though I always think it tastes so much
nicer if you've caught it yourself.

685
00:51:53,577 --> 00:51:54,942
You fish?

686
00:51:55,112 --> 00:51:57,137
I used to when I lived in Ireland.

687
00:51:57,247 --> 00:51:59,545
My father had the most charming
hunting lodge...

688
00:51:59,649 --> 00:52:01,879
on an island in a lake.

689
00:52:01,985 --> 00:52:04,977
- Do you know the west of Ireland?
- Not really.

690
00:52:09,159 --> 00:52:10,888
Whereabouts, exactly?

691
00:52:25,375 --> 00:52:28,708
The Christians go around pretending
they know who God is and how He works.

692
00:52:28,845 --> 00:52:30,710
I've got no time for that tomfoolery.

693
00:52:30,881 --> 00:52:33,714
If you don't know something,
you should stand up and say so...

694
00:52:33,884 --> 00:52:37,615
not go around pretending
you believe in some mumbo jumbo.

695
00:52:37,787 --> 00:52:40,654
I can believe in anything,
provided it's incredible.

696
00:52:40,824 --> 00:52:43,952
That's why I intend to die a Catholic,
though I couldn't possibly live as one.

697
00:52:44,060 --> 00:52:48,292
Catholicism is such a romantic religion.
It has saints and sinners.

698
00:52:49,266 --> 00:52:51,632
The Church of England
only has respectable people...

699
00:52:51,768 --> 00:52:54,134
who believe in respectability.

700
00:52:54,271 --> 00:52:57,263
You get to be a bishop not by what
you believe but by what you don't.

701
00:52:58,775 --> 00:53:00,367
That's true enough.

702
00:53:00,544 --> 00:53:03,035
It's the only church where
the skeptic stands at the altar...

703
00:53:03,180 --> 00:53:06,013
and St. Thomas the Doubter
is prince of the apostles.

704
00:53:06,183 --> 00:53:08,617
No, I couldn't possibly die
in the Church of England.

705
00:53:10,787 --> 00:53:13,312
Where do you stand on cremation?

706
00:53:13,456 --> 00:53:16,220
I'm not sure I have a position.

707
00:53:17,961 --> 00:53:20,327
I'm for it.

708
00:53:20,463 --> 00:53:22,556
I wrote a poem:

709
00:53:22,666 --> 00:53:24,861
''When I am dead, cremate me.''

710
00:53:25,969 --> 00:53:28,199
That's how it begins.

711
00:53:28,305 --> 00:53:31,399
''When I am dead, cremate me.''

712
00:53:31,508 --> 00:53:33,738
What do you think of that
for an opening line?

713
00:53:35,512 --> 00:53:36,877
It's challenging.

714
00:53:37,013 --> 00:53:39,243
I'm a challenging sort of man.

715
00:53:39,349 --> 00:53:41,408
That's why people don't like me.

716
00:53:41,518 --> 00:53:44,180
I don't go along with
the ordinary ways of thinking.

717
00:53:44,354 --> 00:53:46,379
Then we are exactly alike.

718
00:53:47,224 --> 00:53:49,715
Another glass of brandy?

719
00:53:49,859 --> 00:53:52,692
I find that alcohol,
taken in sufficient quantities...

720
00:53:52,862 --> 00:53:55,126
can produce all the effects
of drunkenness.

721
00:53:57,000 --> 00:53:59,298
You were there for ages.

722
00:53:59,436 --> 00:54:03,270
You stayed talking till after 4:00.
I knew you'd like him.

723
00:54:03,440 --> 00:54:06,204
Well, he's got charm,
I admit that.

724
00:54:06,376 --> 00:54:07,741
But that's bad.

725
