cracking the whip downstairs, is he?

917
01:08:37,947 --> 01:08:39,608
- My lord.
- Bosie.

918
01:08:40,783 --> 01:08:43,343
You're not frightened of what
this little man thinks, are you?

919
01:08:43,486 --> 01:08:46,216
I think the pleasures of the evening
should be resumed elsewhere.

920
01:08:52,428 --> 01:08:54,521
You're such a coward.

921
01:08:54,630 --> 01:08:56,723
You say you despise convention...

922
01:08:56,832 --> 01:08:59,130
but you're the most
conventional man I know.

923
01:09:00,436 --> 01:09:03,428
Come on then.
If we're going, let's go.

924
01:09:11,780 --> 01:09:14,044
Until tomorrow, Tommy.

925
01:09:14,150 --> 01:09:16,175
Good-bye, sir.

926
01:09:16,285 --> 01:09:19,584
I goes in, and there's
all this tropical fruit laid out.

927
01:09:24,093 --> 01:09:25,617
Wait a minute, Oscar!

928
01:09:27,096 --> 01:09:31,089
Alfred, how nice to see you.
And Charlie, looking so well.

929
01:09:31,200 --> 01:09:33,600
I'm afraid I'm busy this evening,
but we must have dinner again soon.

930
01:09:33,736 --> 01:09:39,072
It's not a question of dinner.
I got a letter of yours to Lord Alfred.

931
01:09:39,208 --> 01:09:41,870
It's a nice letter, Oscar.
Beautiful.

932
01:09:42,044 --> 01:09:45,775
''Lips like roses. The madness
of kisses in ancient Greece.''

933
01:09:45,948 --> 01:09:48,007
Then I expect
it's one of my prose poems.

934
01:09:48,117 --> 01:09:49,675
