the lies you've been spreading about me?

962
01:11:23,379 --> 01:11:27,475
I've come to tell you
to leave my son alone, you sodomite.

963
01:11:27,583 --> 01:11:31,485
The marquis appears to be very obsessed
with other people's sexual activities.

964
01:11:31,654 --> 01:11:33,554
Has it anything to do
with his new wife...

965
01:11:33,722 --> 01:11:37,158
I wonder, and the fact that she's
seeking divorce for non-consummation?

966
01:11:37,293 --> 01:11:40,285
Unless you swear that you'll have
nothing more to do with Bosie...

967
01:11:40,396 --> 01:11:41,829
I shall go to Scotland Yard.

968
01:11:41,964 --> 01:11:44,262
You can go to the devil.

969
01:11:44,366 --> 01:11:46,766
You and your--
Who is this gargoyle?

970
01:11:46,902 --> 01:11:50,770
You're a queer!
And a sham! A poseur!

971
01:11:50,939 --> 01:11:54,636
If I catch you and Bosie together again,
I'll give you such a thrashing.

972
01:11:55,944 --> 01:11:59,175
I believe Lord Queensberry
once invented some rules for boxing.

973
01:11:59,315 --> 01:12:01,078
I've no idea what they are...

974
01:12:01,250 --> 01:12:03,115
but the Oscar Wilde rule
is to shoot on sight.

975
01:12:03,319 --> 01:12:05,913
- Now, kindly leave my house.
- You can shut up!

976
01:12:06,088 --> 01:12:08,955
I shall leave
when I'm damn well ready.

977
01:12:13,629 --> 01:12:16,154
It's a scandal
what you've been doing.

978
01:12:16,332 --> 01:12:19,460
All the scandal is your own.

979
01:12:19,568 --> 01:12:21,866
Your treatment of your wives...

980
01:12:22,004 --> 01:12:23,835
your neglect of your children...

981
01:12:24,006 --> 01:12:27,271
and, above all,
the depraved insistence...

982
01:12:27,376 --> 01:12:31,369
that they be as tyrannical
and unloving as you are yourself.

983
01:12:32,648 --> 01:12:35,640
Arthur, this is
the Marquis of Queensberry...

984
01:12:35,751 --> 01:12:40,279
the most infamous brute
and the least tender father in London.

985
01:12:40,422 --> 01:12:42,287
Never let him
into my house again.

986
01:12:45,494 --> 01:12:47,325
Very well then.

987
01:12:49,131 --> 01:12:52,123
Let's get out of this stew.

988
01:13:37,079 --> 01:13:39,240
- Out of the way, then!
- I'm sorry, sir!

989
01:13:39,348 --> 01:13:43,216
I'm very sorry,
but it's just not possible!

990
01:13:49,658 --> 01:13:52,456
What are you doing?
Rotten vegetables?

991
01:13:52,628 --> 01:13:54,357
Give that to Oscar Wilde.

992
01:13:54,530 --> 01:13:57,556
Thank you, sir.
We'll take care of it.

993
01:13:57,666 --> 01:14:02,330
I wanted to give it to him
personally as a bouquet.

994
01:14:02,504 --> 01:14:05,405
I daresay you did, sir,
but you're not going to.

995
01:14:06,875 --> 01:14:10,709
He's a cur and a sod!

996
01:14:10,879 --> 01:14:12,471
And a bugger!

997
01:14:12,614 --> 01:14:14,377
You remember that!

998
01:14:17,453 --> 01:14:20,286
I always told you, Gwendolen,
my name is Ernest, didn't I?

999
01:14:20,456 --> 01:14:22,686
Well, it is Ernest after all.

1000
01:14:22,791 --> 01:14:25,851
I mean, it naturally is Ernest.

1001
01:14:25,961 --> 01:14:29,419
Yes, I remember now
that the general was called Ernest.

1002
01:14:29,565 --> 01:14:33,695
I knew I had some particular reason
for disliking the name.

1003
01:14:35,370 --> 01:14:38,828
Ernest! My own Ernest!

1004
01:14:38,974 --> 01:14:42,535
I knew from the first
you could have had no other name.

1005
01:14:42,678 --> 01:14:45,772
Gwendolen, it's a terrible thing
for a man to find out suddenly...

1006
01:14:45,881 --> 01:14:48,748
that all his life he's been
speaking nothing but the truth.

1007
01:14:49,918 --> 01:14:51,749
Can you forgive me?

1008
01:14:51,920 --> 01:14:55,481
I can, for I feel
you are sure to change.

1009
01:14:55,624 --> 01:14:58,115
- My own one!
- Laetitia.

1010
01:14:58,260 --> 01:15:00,091
Frederick! At last!

1011
01:15:00,262 --> 01:15:04,358
- Cecily! At last!
- Gwendolen! At last!

1012
01:15:05,501 --> 01:15:10,768
My nephew, you seem to be
displaying signs of triviality.

1013
01:15:10,906 --> 01:15:13,204
On the contrary, Aunt Augusta...

1014
01:15:13,308 --> 01:15:16,402
I've now realized
for the first time in my life...

1015
01:15:16,512 --> 01:15:19,948
the vital importance
of being earnest.

1016
01:15:48,210 --> 01:15:50,576
Allen, you were wonderful!
Thank you all so much.

1017
01:15:50,712 --> 01:15:53,044
They're calling for you.
You must come on. Curtain, curtain.

1018
01:15:53,181 --> 01:15:55,547
- No, no, George, no, no.
- Come on!

1019
01:16:43,165 --> 01:16:45,531
- Mr. Wilde, sir.
- Yes?

1020
01:16:48,203 --> 01:16:50,034
- For you.
- Thank you.

1021
01:17:01,750 --> 01:17:05,242
''For Oscar Wilde...

1022
01:17:05,387 --> 01:17:06,684
Ponce,'' is it?

1023
01:17:06,822 --> 01:17:09,086
''Ponce and 'somdomite.'''

1024
01:17:09,191 --> 01:17:13,321
''Posing as a sodomite.''
He's illiterate-- illiterate, ignorant.

1025
01:17:13,428 --> 01:17:16,420
- It's hideous.
- We've got him now, Robbie.

1026
01:17:16,531 --> 01:17:18,328
He wrote it down.
The porter read it.

1027
01:17:18,500 --> 01:17:21,196
That makes it a public libel.
Now we can take him to court.

1028
01:17:21,370 --> 01:17:23,395
For God's sake.

1029
01:17:26,708 --> 01:17:29,700
Oscar, you mustn't do that.
That would be-- I mean--

1030
01:17:29,811 --> 01:17:32,143
We've just been waiting for a chance
to get him in the dock...

1031
01:17:32,280 --> 01:17:35,044
and show the world what a swine
and shit he's always been.

1032
01:17:35,217 --> 01:17:39,051
- To me, my mother, my brothers.
- But he'll plead justification.

1033
01:17:39,221 --> 01:17:41,883
He'll call all the renters
as witnesses for the defense.

1034
01:17:42,057 --> 01:17:44,787
Of course he won't.
He doesn't know what a renter is.

1035
01:17:44,960 --> 01:17:49,397
I hear he's had detectives following you
ever since you came back from Egypt.

1036
01:17:49,531 --> 01:17:52,091
He can't prove anything.
But we can.

1037
01:17:53,502 --> 01:17:55,697
We can prove he's the vilest man
that ever walked the earth.

1038
01:17:55,804 --> 01:17:57,635
Tear the card up, Oscar.
Pretend you never got it.

1039
01:17:57,806 --> 01:18:00,798
Are you mad?
That's our main piece of evidence.

1040
01:18:00,909 --> 01:18:03,400
I'm sure if Oscar went abroad
for a few months...

1041
01:18:03,545 --> 01:18:05,570
lived on royalties
while your father calms down--

1042
01:18:05,681 --> 01:18:08,275
- Whose side are you on?
- Bosie, if this goes to court...

1043
01:18:08,417 --> 01:18:10,408
Oscar will have to tell lies...

1044
01:18:10,519 --> 01:18:13,283
perjure himself--
everything will come out.

1045
01:18:13,455 --> 01:18:16,185
Whatever the result,
it will be utter disaster.

1046
01:18:16,358 --> 01:18:17,950
You're an enemy then.

1047
01:18:18,093 --> 01:18:22,086
No, no, Bosie, please.
Robbie...

1048
01:18:22,197 --> 01:18:25,724
you're a dear boy, but I can't
even think of leaving the country.

1049
01:18:25,867 --> 01:18:30,930
As a matter of fact, I can't even
leave this hotel. I can't pay the bill.

1050
01:18:31,039 --> 01:18:33,701
We can raise you money,
for heaven's sake.

1051
01:18:33,875 --> 01:18:36,469
Anyway, what about
your royalties?

1052
01:18:36,611 --> 01:18:38,511
We shall need all the money
we can get for the libel case.

1053
01:18:39,815 --> 01:18:43,216
My father can't go on making
all our lives a torment like this.

1054
01:18:44,486 --> 01:18:46,386
Oscar, I beg you.

1055
01:18:47,556 --> 01:18:49,148
I'm not going to run away, Robbie.

1056
01:18:49,324 --> 01:18:52,623
I'm not going to hide.
That would be the English thing to do.

1057
01:18:52,761 --> 01:18:56,197
If you take Queensberry to court,
all hell will break loose.

1058
01:18:56,331 --> 01:18:59,858
All my life I've fought
against the English vice:

1059
01:19:00,001 --> 01:19:02,868
hypocrisy--
not that that's the point.

1060
01:19:03,038 --> 01:19:07,407
The point is, Queensberry's already
caused the death of one of his sons.

1061
01:19:07,542 --> 01:19:11,444
If I don't try and stop him now,
whom will he harm next?

1062
01:19:13,582 --> 01:19:15,413
<i>He's avoiding me, Robbie.</i>

1063
01:19:16,752 --> 01:19:20,415
I know what everyone's saying,
but it's not true.

1064
01:19:20,589 --> 01:19:22,420
It's not true.

1065
01:19:24,126 --> 01:19:27,220
- Is it?
- Of course not.

1066
01:19:28,797 --> 01:19:30,662
Oh, it's so shaming.

1067
01:19:32,534 --> 01:19:36,800
No, I find it easier to stand.

1068
01:19:36,905 --> 01:19:41,205
I'm going to Torquay for a month,
try to get my back right.

1069
01:19:41,309 --> 01:19:44,745
- Oscar's been so busy--
- I'm sure he'll be terribly upset...

1070
01:19:44,880 --> 01:19:48,281
when he knows you've been
in so much pain.

1071
01:19:49,718 --> 01:19:53,552
The truth is,
I need some money.

1072
01:19:53,722 --> 01:19:57,488
Not even sure where he is
to ask for it.

1073
01:19:57,659 --> 01:20:00,389
It does seem rather hard when he's
having such an extraordinary success.

1074
01:20:00,562 --> 01:20:02,086
I think I can find him.

1075
01:20:05,901 --> 01:20:08,369
I keep hearing these stories
about Bosie and his father.

1076
01:20:08,503 --> 01:20:12,803
- I'm sure you don't want to--
- Oh, yes. I do.

1077
01:20:14,676 --> 01:20:19,170
Men think women should be
protected by not knowing.

1078
01:20:19,314 --> 01:20:21,680
Not knowing only makes it worse.

1079
01:20:24,753 --> 01:20:27,483
Is there going to be trouble?

1080
01:20:29,758 --> 01:20:31,453
I hope not.

1081
01:20:33,528 --> 01:20:35,962
<i>I believe a prosecution
would certainly succeed...</i>

1082
01:20:36,097 --> 01:20:37,962
provided--
and I stress this--

1083
01:20:38,133 --> 01:20:42,001
provided there is no truth whatever in
the accusation made by Lord Queensberry.

1084
01:20:42,170 --> 01:20:44,001
Of course
there's no truth in it.

1085
01:20:46,107 --> 01:20:51,204
Then so long as I have Mr. Wilde's
assurance that that is indeed the case.

1086
01:21:00,889 --> 01:21:03,585
There is no truth
in the accusation whatever.

1087
01:21:04,793 --> 01:21:08,456
Good. Excellent.

1088
01:21:10,165 --> 01:21:13,225
The defense, I understand,
will be led by Mr. Edward Carson.

1089
01:21:14,002 --> 01:21:17,995
Old Ned? I was at college
with him in Dublin.

1090
01:21:18,106 --> 01:21:22,509
No doubt he will perform his task with
all the bitterness of an old friend.

1091
01:21:24,679 --> 01:21:27,273
In writing a book or a play,
I'm concerned entirely with literature--

1092
01:21:27,415 --> 01:21:31,545
with art-- I do not aim
at doing good or evil...

1093
01:21:31,653 --> 01:21:33,917
but at making a thing that will have
some quality of beauty.

1094
01:21:34,022 --> 01:21:39,358
Well, listen, sir. Here is
one of your pieces of literature.

1095
01:21:39,494 --> 01:21:42,258
''Wickedness is a myth
invented by good people...

1096
01:21:42,430 --> 01:21:44,728
to account for the curious
attractiveness of others.''

1097
01:21:49,504 --> 01:21:51,028
Do you think that true?

1098
01:21:51,172 --> 01:21:53,538
Oh, I rarely think
anything I write is true.

1099
01:21:53,675 --> 01:21:59,272
''If one tells the truth, one is sure,
sooner or later, to be found out.''

1100
01:22:02,183 --> 01:22:05,778
That is a pleasing paradox, but
I do not set store by it as an axiom.

1101
01:22:05,921 --> 01:22:08,321
Is it good for the young?

1102
01:22:08,456 --> 01:22:11,687
Anything is good that stimulates
thought, at whatever age.

1103
01:22:11,793 --> 01:22:13,624
Whether moral or immoral?

1104
01:22:13,795 --> 01:22:16,662
There's no such thing
as morality or immorality in thought.

1105
01:22:16,831 --> 01:22:18,423
What about this then?

1106
01:22:19,868 --> 01:22:22,268
''Pleasure is the only thing
one should live for.''

1107
01:22:24,406 --> 01:22:27,898
I think that the realization of
one's self is the prime aim of life...

1108
01:22:28,043 --> 01:22:32,343
and that to realize through pleasure is
finer than to do so through pain.

1109
01:22:32,447 --> 01:22:36,315
I am, on this point, entirely on
the side of the ancients, the Greeks.

1110
01:22:39,354 --> 01:22:42,517
<i>How long have you known
Alfred Taylor?</i>

1111
01:22:42,624 --> 01:22:45,457
<i>About two years,
two-and-a-half years.</i>

1112
01:22:45,627 --> 01:22:49,324
- Is he an intimate friend of yours?
- I wouldn't call him that, no.

1113
01:22:49,497 --> 01:22:52,022
But you went often to his rooms?

1114
01:22:52,167 --> 01:22:54,465
About seven or eight times,
perhaps.

1115
01:22:54,569 --> 01:22:58,801
Did you know Mr. Taylor kept
ladies' dresses in his rooms?

1116
01:23:01,810 --> 01:23:06,577
Did you know he was notorious
for introducing young men to older men?

1117
01:23:06,748 --> 01:23:09,979
I never heard it in my life.

1118
01:23:10,085 --> 01:23:11,985
Has he introduced
young men to you?

1119
01:23:13,154 --> 01:23:14,985
Yes.

1120
01:23:15,156 --> 01:23:18,683
- How many young men?
- About five.

1121
01:23:18,827 --> 01:23:23,423
- What were their occupations?
- I really don't know.

1122
01:23:23,565 --> 01:23:26,159
Oh, well, let me tell you,
Mr. Wilde.

1123
01:23:26,334 --> 01:23:30,134
You met a man called
Charles Parker there, I believe.

1124
01:23:30,305 --> 01:23:31,363
Yes.

1125
01:23:31,473 --> 01:23:34,237
Charles Parker is...

1126
01:23:34,409 --> 01:23:36,240
a gentleman's valet.

1127
01:23:37,812 --> 01:23:39,643
You met his brother there
too, I believe.

1128
01:23:39,814 --> 01:23:42,078
- Yes.
- He is a groom.

1129
01:23:44,185 --> 01:23:46,483
I didn't care tuppence
what they were.

1130
01:23:46,588 --> 01:23:51,184
I liked them. I have a passion
to civilize the community.

1131
01:23:51,359 --> 01:23:55,659
I recognize no social distinctions
at all of any kind.

1132
01:23:55,797 --> 01:23:57,788
To me, youth--
the mere fact of youth--

1133
01:23:57,899 --> 01:24:02,063
is so wonderful that I would sooner
talk to a young man for half an hour...

1134
01:24:02,170 --> 01:24:06,539
than, well, than be
cross-examined in court.

1135
01:24:06,674 --> 01:24:09,666
So, do I understand that...

1136
01:24:09,778 --> 01:24:13,214
even a boy you might pick up in the
street would be a pleasing companion?

1137
01:24:13,348 --> 01:24:17,546
I would talk to a street Arab
with pleasure if he would talk to me.

1138
01:24:17,652 --> 01:24:19,483
- And take him to your rooms?
- Yes.

1139
01:24:19,654 --> 01:24:22,214
And then commit
improprieties with him?

1140
01:24:24,092 --> 01:24:25,320
Certainly not.

1141
01:24:28,963 --> 01:24:32,558
<i>You withdraw your libel action
against Lord Queensberry.</i>

1142
01:24:32,734 --> 01:24:34,634
Well and good.

1143
01:24:34,803 --> 01:24:38,102
But there remains the question
of the evidence--

1144
01:24:38,239 --> 01:24:41,697
Lord Queensberry's evidence
against you.

1145
01:24:41,843 --> 01:24:46,075
My information is that the Crown
wishes to pursue the matter.

1146
01:24:47,582 --> 01:24:52,610
In which case, an arrest
and a charge of gross indecency...

1147
01:24:52,720 --> 01:24:54,711
are certain to follow.

1148
01:24:54,823 --> 01:24:58,657
The maximum sentence
is two years hard labor.

1149
01:24:58,827 --> 01:25:02,695
Nine months hard labor
is reckoned to be more...

1150
01:25:02,864 --> 01:25:04,695
than a man of our background...

1151
01:25:04,866 --> 01:25:06,595
can survive.

1152
01:25:09,370 --> 01:25:11,235
The children, the boys--

1153
01:25:11,406 --> 01:25:14,398
- I must go and see them.
- You have no time for that.

1154
01:25:14,509 --> 01:25:18,809
But my wife--
I have to say good-bye to my wife.

1155
01:25:18,947 --> 01:25:21,541
Unless you positively wish
to subject her...

1156
01:25:21,716 --> 01:25:24,014
to the further humiliation
of seeing you arrested...

1157
01:25:24,119 --> 01:25:27,350
and taken away
in front of the gutter press...

1158
01:25:27,455 --> 01:25:29,286
<i>Mr. Wilde,you must go.</i>

1159
01:25:36,131 --> 01:25:40,295
Oscar, you must take that train.

1160
01:25:40,401 --> 01:25:43,268
Practically everyone
you know will be on it.

1161
01:25:43,438 --> 01:25:47,966
At least 600 single gentlemen,
all in abject terror of arrest.

1162
01:25:52,714 --> 01:25:56,411
Where your life leads you,
you must go.

1163
01:25:57,585 --> 01:25:59,644
<i>I defy society.</i>

1164
01:25:59,754 --> 01:26:01,278
Tell him to go.

1165
01:26:03,224 --> 01:26:05,590
He must save himself.

1166
01:26:07,428 --> 01:26:09,419
Tell him to go abroad.

1167
01:26:09,531 --> 01:26:11,692
I've been telling him all day.

1168
01:26:13,301 --> 01:26:14,928
He won't budge.

1169
01:26:22,110 --> 01:26:26,342
People have never understood
the courage he needed to be himself.

1170
01:26:26,447 --> 01:26:28,574
You must go abroad too.

1171
01:26:28,683 --> 01:26:31,777
We must all go abroad at once.

1172
01:26:34,289 --> 01:26:36,450
Oscar says, will you
tell the boys good-bye.

1173
01:26:39,127 --> 01:26:41,721
I need to go through his papers.

1174
01:26:44,999 --> 01:26:48,662
You know,
I was always too silent.

1175
01:26:48,836 --> 01:26:50,667
If I'd known--

1176
01:26:56,277 --> 01:26:58,268
If I'd only spoken up.

1177
01:26:58,379 --> 01:27:00,472
It wouldn't have made
any difference.

1178
01:27:02,217 --> 01:27:03,775
Perhaps not...

1179
01:27:04,953 --> 01:27:08,047
but at least I wouldn't
blame myself now.

1180
01:27:31,713 --> 01:27:34,978
<i>You're an Irish gentleman.
Of course,you must stay.</i>

1181
01:27:35,083 --> 01:27:37,381
Your father fought
when he was libeled.

1182
01:27:37,485 --> 01:27:40,318
<i>- I was in the courts myself. I fought--
- Yes, I know, Madre.</i>

1183
01:27:40,488 --> 01:27:44,219
You will fight these
English philistines, and you'll win.

1184
01:27:44,392 --> 01:27:49,091
And even if you lose--
if you go to prison--

1185
01:27:49,264 --> 01:27:52,256
you'll always be my son.

1186
01:27:52,367 --> 01:27:54,665
Of course, it's too late
to change that now.

1187
01:27:56,170 --> 01:27:57,831
If you go, Oscar...

1188
01:27:58,006 --> 01:28:00,338
I'll never speak to you again.

1189
01:28:00,475 --> 01:28:03,672
No one will ever speak
to me again, whatever I do.

1190
01:28:05,446 --> 01:28:08,677
<i>Of course I'm your son, Madre...</i>

1191
01:28:08,783 --> 01:28:12,014
which is why,
even if I lose...

1192
01:28:12,120 --> 01:28:14,418
the English
will never forget me.

1193
01:28:17,492 --> 01:28:19,016
My darling.

1194
01:28:48,256 --> 01:28:50,622
Get out of my way.
Get out! Out!

1195
01:28:51,993 --> 01:28:53,824
Take me away at once!

1196
01:29:02,203 --> 01:29:04,296
Lady Wilde. Lady Wilde!

1197
01:29:04,405 --> 01:29:07,272
Have you anything to say about
your son's disgrace, Lady Wilde?

1198
01:29:07,442 --> 01:29:09,273
<i>Have you anything to say?</i>

1199
01:29:16,951 --> 01:29:18,316
Come in.

1200
01:29:25,159 --> 01:29:27,024
Mr. Wilde, I believe.

1201
01:29:28,629 --> 01:29:29,687
Yes, yes.

1202
01:29:29,797 --> 01:29:31,992
We have a warrant here
for your arrest...

1203
01:29:32,100 --> 01:29:35,001
on a charge
of committing indecent acts.

1204
01:29:43,044 --> 01:29:45,205
<i>I recommend Switzerland
as soon as possible.</i>

1205
01:29:45,313 --> 01:29:48,146
You will have to change
your name, of course.

1206
01:29:50,618 --> 01:29:51,846
I can't.

1207
01:29:51,953 --> 01:29:54,513
My dear Constance,
the name of Wilde will be...

1208
01:29:54,655 --> 01:29:56,714
a word of execration
for the next thousand years.

1209
01:29:56,824 --> 01:30:00,419
You can't possibly let your boys grow up
with people knowing who they are.

1210
01:30:00,561 --> 01:30:02,392
Think of their lives at school.

1211
01:30:02,563 --> 01:30:04,929
Thank you for your advice.

1212
01:30:06,334 --> 01:30:08,461
I'm sorry our friendship
has to end like this.

1213
01:30:08,569 --> 01:30:12,733
- Oh, you will always be my friend.
- I am still Oscar's wife.

1214
01:30:12,840 --> 01:30:17,106
That must cease forthwith.
Forthwith. Do you understand?

1215
01:30:17,211 --> 01:30:20,009
Anybody who has anything
to do with Oscar from now on...

1216
01:30:20,181 --> 01:30:23,048
will never be received
in society again--

1217
01:30:23,217 --> 01:30:24,445
ever.

1218
01:30:29,624 --> 01:30:33,754
Oh, God, Ada.
What is going to happen to him?

1219
01:30:42,270 --> 01:30:44,329
That's Oscar Wilde's boy.

1220
01:30:44,439 --> 01:30:46,930
Oscar, you must let me
in the witness box.

1221
01:30:47,074 --> 01:30:49,406
If the jury can only hear
what I have to say--

1222
01:30:49,544 --> 01:30:51,705
Bosie, darling boy.

1223
01:30:51,813 --> 01:30:54,714
As soon as they see you
in all your golden youth...

1224
01:30:54,882 --> 01:30:57,009
and me in all my corruption--

1225
01:30:57,118 --> 01:31:00,451
You didn't corrupt me.
I corrupted you, if anything.

1226
01:31:00,588 --> 01:31:02,419
That's not how it will seem.

1227
01:31:02,590 --> 01:31:05,787
But I must have my say.
It's outrageous.

1228
01:31:05,893 --> 01:31:08,987
Everyone else has said everything,
anything that came into his head.

1229
01:31:09,096 --> 01:31:11,690
But I'm the person
all this is about.

1230
01:31:11,866 --> 01:31:14,266
It's me my father wants
to get at, not you.

1231
01:31:14,402 --> 01:31:16,768
It's outrageous
that I can't have my say.

1232
01:31:16,904 --> 01:31:21,307
It won't help, Bosie.
It may actually make things worse.

1233
01:31:21,476 --> 01:31:25,970
But my father will win.
I can't endure my father winning.

1234
01:31:27,782 --> 01:31:29,977
You must go away, dear boy.

1235
01:31:30,084 --> 01:31:32,678
I couldn't bear for them
to arrest you.

1236
01:31:36,491 --> 01:31:39,085
I can't bear what they're
saying about you in court.

1237
01:31:42,263 --> 01:31:44,163
Jesus Christ.

1238
01:31:46,267 --> 01:31:48,394
Good-bye, Bosie, dear boy.

1239
01:31:48,503 --> 01:31:51,666
Don't let anyone, anything,
ever change your feeling for me...

1240
01:31:51,772 --> 01:31:53,364
change your love.

1241
01:31:53,508 --> 01:31:56,341
- See you next time.
- Time's up, my lord.

1242
01:31:56,511 --> 01:32:00,845
Oscar, never. They never will.
I won't let them.

1243
01:32:11,626 --> 01:32:14,220
<i>You've been a great deal
in the company of Lord Alfred Douglas?</i>

1244
01:32:14,395 --> 01:32:15,760
Oh, yes.

1245
01:32:17,265 --> 01:32:20,291
- Did he read his poems to you?
- Yes.

1246
01:32:20,401 --> 01:32:23,700
So, you can perhaps
understand that...

1247
01:32:23,838 --> 01:32:26,136
some of his verses...

1248
01:32:26,274 --> 01:32:31,712
would not be acceptable to a reader
with an ordinary balance to mind?

1249
01:32:32,647 --> 01:32:34,444
I'm not prepared to say.

1250
01:32:34,615 --> 01:32:37,709
It's a question of taste
and temperament...

1251
01:32:37,818 --> 01:32:39,945
and individuality.

1252
01:32:40,054 --> 01:32:43,080
I should say that one man's poetry
is another man's poison.

1253
01:32:43,190 --> 01:32:45,590
Yes, I daresay.

1254
01:32:45,726 --> 01:32:48,251
But in this poem
by Lord Alfred Douglas...

1255
01:32:48,396 --> 01:32:50,728
''Two Loves''...

1256
01:32:50,865 --> 01:32:52,696
there is one love,
true love...

1257
01:32:52,867 --> 01:32:56,496
which-- and I quote--

1258
01:32:56,671 --> 01:33:00,300
''fills the hearts of boy and girl
with mutual flame.''

1259
01:33:00,474 --> 01:33:04,638
And, there is another:

1260
01:33:04,745 --> 01:33:09,114
''I am the love
that dare not speak its name.''

1261
01:33:11,319 --> 01:33:13,344
Was that poem explained to you?

1262
01:33:14,455 --> 01:33:17,788
- I think it's clear.
- There's no doubt as to what it means?

1263
01:33:17,925 --> 01:33:19,517
Most certainly not.

1264
01:33:19,694 --> 01:33:22,561
So, is it not clear
that the love described...

1265
01:33:22,730 --> 01:33:26,359
relates to natural
and unnatural love?

1266
01:33:30,871 --> 01:33:34,967
Then what is the love
that dare not speak its name?

1267
01:33:47,555 --> 01:33:51,252
The love that dare not
speak its name...

1268
01:33:51,425 --> 01:33:53,950
in this century...

1269
01:33:54,095 --> 01:33:56,620
is such a great affection...

1270
01:33:56,764 --> 01:34:00,200
of an elder for a younger man...

1271
01:34:00,334 --> 01:34:02,802
as there was between
David and Jonathan...

1272
01:34:02,937 --> 01:34:07,704
such as Plato made
the very basis of his philosophy...

1273
01:34:07,875 --> 01:34:11,538
and such as you may find in
the sonnets of Michelangelo...

1274
01:34:11,712 --> 01:34:13,145
and Shakespeare.

1275
01:34:15,483 --> 01:34:19,977
It is, in this century,
misunderstood--

1276
01:34:20,121 --> 01:34:23,613
so much misunderstood
that it may be described as...

1277
01:34:23,758 --> 01:34:26,488
the love that dare not
speak its name.

1278
01:34:26,661 --> 01:34:30,256
And, on account of it,
I am placed where I am now.

1279
01:34:31,999 --> 01:34:35,059
It is beautiful.
It is fine.

1280
01:34:36,437 --> 01:34:38,871
It is the noblest form
of affection.

1281
01:34:40,007 --> 01:34:42,532
There's nothing unnatural
about it.

1282
01:34:44,578 --> 01:34:46,978
It is intellectual...

1283
01:34:47,114 --> 01:34:50,880
and it repeatedly exists
between an elder and a younger man...

1284
01:34:51,052 --> 01:34:54,783
when the elder has intellect...

1285
01:34:54,955 --> 01:34:57,389
and the younger man...

1286
01:34:57,525 --> 01:35:02,121
has all the joy, hope
and glamour of life before him.

1287
01:35:03,964 --> 01:35:08,867
That it should be so,
the world does not understand.

1288
01:35:09,036 --> 01:35:11,061
The world mocks at it...

1289
01:35:11,172 --> 01:35:15,302
and sometimes puts one
in the pillory for it.

1290
01:35:34,128 --> 01:35:37,188
The crime of which
you have been convicted...

1291
01:35:37,298 --> 01:35:39,391
is so bad...

1292
01:35:39,500 --> 01:35:42,799
that I shall pass
the severest sentence...

1293
01:35:42,903 --> 01:35:46,168
that the law will allow.

1294
01:35:46,273 --> 01:35:51,074
In my judgment, it is totally
inadequate for such a case as this.

1295
01:35:52,279 --> 01:35:55,373
It is the worst case
I have ever tried!

1296
01:35:55,483 --> 01:35:58,213
The sentence of the court...

1297
01:35:58,385 --> 01:36:00,580
is that you will be imprisoned...

1298
01:36:00,688 --> 01:36:03,953
<i>and held to hard labor...</i>

1299
01:36:04,058 --> 01:36:06,754
<i>- Stand aside, please.
- for two years.</i>

1300
01:36:06,927 --> 01:36:08,758
- Shame.
- Pervert.

1301
01:36:14,301 --> 01:36:15,529
Pervert!

1302
01:36:22,676 --> 01:36:24,507
Shame on you!

1303
01:36:44,999 --> 01:36:46,523
Disgusting!

1304
01:37:12,259 --> 01:37:15,558
<i>A slim thing,
gold-haired like an angel...</i>

1305
01:37:15,663 --> 01:37:18,063
<i>stands always at my side.</i>

1306
01:37:18,199 --> 01:37:21,965
<i>He moves in the gloom
like a white flower.</i>

1307
01:37:22,136 --> 01:37:26,505
<i>I thought but to defend him from
his father. I thought of nothing else.</i>

1308
01:37:42,957 --> 01:37:45,585
<i>Now my life seems
to have gone from me.</i>

1309
01:37:45,759 --> 01:37:48,057
<i>I'm caught in a terrible net.</i>

1310
01:37:48,195 --> 01:37:50,925
<i>But so long as I think
he is thinking of me--</i>

1311
01:37:51,098 --> 01:37:55,558
<i>my sweet rose, my delicate flower,
my lily of lilies--</i>

1312
01:37:55,703 --> 01:37:59,764
<i>it is in prison that I shall
test the power of love.</i>

1313
01:37:59,874 --> 01:38:03,071
<i>I shall see if I can't make
the bitter waters sweet...</i>

1314
01:38:03,177 --> 01:38:05,577
<i>by the intensity of the love
I bear you.</i>

1315
01:38:19,159 --> 01:38:23,459
<i>He asked me not to change.
Those were his last words to me--</i>

1316
01:38:23,597 --> 01:38:25,588
''Don't change.''

1317
01:38:25,699 --> 01:38:29,294
Well, things are going to have
to change when he comes out.

1318
01:38:30,471 --> 01:38:32,666
He'll have no money at all.

1319
01:38:32,773 --> 01:38:35,401
- So you're blaming me, too, are you?
- I'm not blaming anyone.

1320
01:38:35,576 --> 01:38:39,171
Bosie, you're not the only person
on this earth Oscar cares about.

1321
01:38:40,347 --> 01:38:43,373
You've always hated me,
Robbie...

1322
01:38:43,484 --> 01:38:46,885
because Oscar loved and still loves me
when you were just one of his boys.

1323
01:38:56,764 --> 01:38:59,597
I'm suffering just as much
as he is, you know.

1324
01:39:01,468 --> 01:39:03,197
My life's ruined too.

1325
01:39:03,370 --> 01:39:07,807
I'm much younger than he is. I've hardly
had any life, and it's ruined already.

1326
01:39:07,942 --> 01:39:11,639
When Oscar gets out,
we'll live together properly.

1327
01:39:11,812 --> 01:39:15,509
We'll take a villa
somewhere near here-- Posilipo...

1328
01:39:15,683 --> 01:39:18,311
- or Ischia.
- Or Capri.

1329
01:39:20,421 --> 01:39:22,821
I'll take care of him.

1330
01:39:22,957 --> 01:39:25,323
I'll give him
everything he wants.

1331
01:39:26,627 --> 01:39:28,686
I love him, Robbie.

1332
01:39:31,131 --> 01:39:33,656
Oscar's mine,
and I'm going to have him.

1333
01:39:50,417 --> 01:39:55,252
<i>''Years went over, and the giant
grew very old and very feeble.</i>

1334
01:39:55,422 --> 01:39:59,324
<i>He couldn't play about anymore,
so he sat in a huge armchair...</i>

1335
01:39:59,493 --> 01:40:03,088
<i>and watched the children at their games
and admired his garden.</i>

1336
01:40:07,735 --> 01:40:10,226
<i>'I have many beautiful flowers, '
he said.</i>

1337
01:40:10,371 --> 01:40:14,171
<i>'But the children are
the most beautiful flowers of all. '''</i>

1338
01:40:52,513 --> 01:40:55,107
I'm afraid Cyril has got
some idea why you're here.

1339
01:40:56,750 --> 01:40:59,116
I'm sending him
to school in Germany.

1340
01:41:01,989 --> 01:41:04,355
I can't manage them on my own.

1341
01:41:08,162 --> 01:41:10,892
Your back isn't better then?

1342
01:41:11,065 --> 01:41:12,896
No, not really.

1343
01:41:14,735 --> 01:41:17,101
I may have to have an operation.

1344
01:41:19,073 --> 01:41:22,600
What I've done
to you and the boys--

1345
01:41:22,743 --> 01:41:24,608
I can't--

1346
01:41:24,778 --> 01:41:27,611
I shall never forgive myself.

1347
01:41:30,150 --> 01:41:32,778
If we could choose
our natures--

1348
01:41:35,255 --> 01:41:37,416
If we could only choose.

1349
01:41:37,524 --> 01:41:39,355
But it's no use.

1350
01:41:42,429 --> 01:41:46,263
Whatever our natures are,
we must fulfill them...

1351
01:41:47,634 --> 01:41:49,727
or our lives-- my life--

1352
01:41:49,837 --> 01:41:53,295
would have been filled
with dishonesty.

1353
01:41:55,709 --> 01:41:58,542
Even more dishonesty
than there actually was.

1354
01:42:03,951 --> 01:42:06,317
I've always loved you,
Constance.

1355
01:42:08,422 --> 01:42:09,946
You must believe me.

1356
01:42:12,192 --> 01:42:14,683
I don't see
how you can have done--

1357
01:42:14,828 --> 01:42:16,659
not truly.

1358
01:42:17,865 --> 01:42:19,662
Not if all the time--

1359
01:42:19,833 --> 01:42:21,357
I didn't know.

1360
01:42:24,404 --> 01:42:26,770
''Know thyself,''
I used to say.

1361
01:42:28,742 --> 01:42:31,267
I didn't know myself.

1362
01:42:32,913 --> 01:42:34,744
I didn't know.

1363
01:42:38,152 --> 01:42:40,484
I suppose you want a divorce.

1364
01:42:42,956 --> 01:42:44,480
You have every reason.

1365
01:42:48,162 --> 01:42:51,529
I've been thinking,
when you do come out--

1366
01:42:51,665 --> 01:42:54,463
when they let you out--
you can go to Switzerland or Italy...

1367
01:42:54,635 --> 01:42:57,468
write another play,
get yourself back.

1368
01:42:58,705 --> 01:43:01,230
You can.

1369
01:43:01,375 --> 01:43:04,139
You're so clever.
You can.

1370
01:43:14,821 --> 01:43:16,880
I don't want a divorce.

1371
01:43:21,395 --> 01:43:24,125
Will you ever let me
see the children again?

1372
01:43:25,832 --> 01:43:27,060
Of course.

1373
01:43:34,408 --> 01:43:36,239
But there must be one condition:

1374
01:43:40,280 --> 01:43:42,578
Oscar, you must never
see Bosie again.

1375
01:43:44,384 --> 01:43:48,582
If I saw Bosie now,
I'd kill him.

1376
01:43:52,793 --> 01:43:54,988
The children love you, Oscar.

1377
01:44:03,837 --> 01:44:06,431
They'll always love you.

1378
01:44:15,315 --> 01:44:17,749
Did anyone tell you?

1379
01:44:17,884 --> 01:44:20,444
<i>They've been performing
Salome in Paris.</i>

1380
01:44:29,463 --> 01:44:33,263
<i>''The giant hastened across the grass
and came near to the child.</i>

1381
01:44:33,433 --> 01:44:36,095
<i>And when he came quite close,
his face grew red with anger.</i>

1382
01:44:36,270 --> 01:44:40,673
<i>And he said,
'Who hath dared to wound thee?'</i>

1383
01:44:40,807 --> 01:44:44,004
<i>For on the palms of the child's hands
were the prints of two nails.</i>

1384
01:44:44,111 --> 01:44:46,944
<i>And the prints of two nails
were on his little feet.</i>

1385
01:45:03,130 --> 01:45:07,396
<i>'Who hath dared to wound thee?'
cried the giant.</i>

1386
01:45:07,501 --> 01:45:11,198
<i>'Tell me, that I may take
my big sword and slay him. '</i>

1387
01:45:11,371 --> 01:45:13,601
<i>'Nay, 'answered the child.</i>

1388
01:45:13,707 --> 01:45:16,073
<i>'For these are
the wounds of love. '''</i>

1389
01:45:24,618 --> 01:45:27,109
Bosie thinks I'm jealous.

1390
01:45:27,254 --> 01:45:29,313
I think it will come as a shock
to Bosie to realize...

1391
01:45:29,423 --> 01:45:32,324
that even he is relatively unimportant
in the scheme of things.

1392
01:45:32,492 --> 01:45:36,485
But, no doubt, Bosie will be
remembered as long as Oscar...

1393
01:45:36,596 --> 01:45:38,257
unfortunately.

1394
01:45:43,804 --> 01:45:45,635
I sometimes wonder...

1395
01:45:48,775 --> 01:45:50,606
if I hadn't...

1396
01:45:54,247 --> 01:45:55,976
pushed him into--

1397
01:45:56,149 --> 01:45:57,377
Don't.

1398
01:45:59,119 --> 01:46:01,553
Oscar was very lucky
to meet you, Robbie.

1399
01:46:02,422 --> 01:46:04,287
Think who else
it might have been.

1400
01:46:05,459 --> 01:46:07,654
Oh, I'll have that one.
Thank you.

1401
01:46:07,761 --> 01:46:11,629
- Must you go abroad again at once?
- I shouldn't be here now.

1402
01:46:14,468 --> 01:46:17,494
But has he got anywhere to go
when he's released?

1403
01:46:17,604 --> 01:46:19,401
It'll have to be in France.

1404
01:46:19,573 --> 01:46:22,269
I'm going to see
what I can arrange.

1405
01:46:22,442 --> 01:46:24,637
But here...

1406
01:46:24,745 --> 01:46:26,770
when he leaves prison--

1407
01:46:32,719 --> 01:46:34,880
- Good-bye, Mr. Harris.
- Good-bye, sir.

1408
01:46:34,988 --> 01:46:37,354
Good-bye, Mr. Snow.
Thank you.

1409
01:46:43,397 --> 01:46:45,592
My dear Sphinx.

1410
01:46:47,667 --> 01:46:50,500
How marvelous of you to know what hat
to wear at 7:00 in the morning...

1411
01:46:50,670 --> 01:46:53,571
to meet a friend
who's been away.

1412
01:46:53,740 --> 01:46:56,607
- No, I'll keep this.
- What is it.

1413
01:46:56,777 --> 01:46:59,371
It's a letter to Bosie
telling him...

1414
01:46:59,513 --> 01:47:01,708
how I love him
but can never see him again.

1415
01:47:01,815 --> 01:47:04,682
I'm going to ask Robbie
to have it copied out before I send it.

1416
01:47:04,851 --> 01:47:08,184
I rather fear Bosie
might throw it on the fire.

1417
01:47:08,321 --> 01:47:11,586
<i>I call it De Profundis.
It comes from the very depths.</i>

1418
01:47:46,827 --> 01:47:49,227
<i>''I know not whether laws
be right...</i>

1419
01:47:49,362 --> 01:47:51,762
<i>or whether laws be wrong.</i>

1420
01:47:51,898 --> 01:47:54,025
<i>All that we know
who lie in jail...</i>

1421
01:47:54,134 --> 01:47:56,295
<i>is that the wall is strong...</i>

1422
01:47:56,403 --> 01:47:59,531
<i>and that each day
is like a year--</i>

1423
01:47:59,639 --> 01:48:02,005
<i>a year whose days are long.</i>

1424
01:48:06,746 --> 01:48:10,341
<i>Yet each man kills
